| 66 | No. 19 Louisville | 69\n| February 2, 2005 | Freedom Hall | No. 18 Cincinnati | 70 | No. 9 Louisville | 77\n| January 25, 2006 | Freedom Hall | Cincinnati | 50 | No. 22 Louisville | 67\n| February 6, 2006 | Fifth Third Arena | Cincinnati | 74 | Louisville | 68\n| January 31, 2007 | Fifth Third Arena | Cincinnati | 53 | Louisville | 69\n| January 1, 2008 | Freedom Hall | Cincinnati | 58 | Louisville | 57\n| February 21, 2009 | Fifth Third Arena | Cincinnati | 63 | No. 7 Louisville | 72\n| January 24, 2010 | [[KFC Yum! Center]] | Cincinnati | 60 | Louisville | 68\n| [[2010 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|March 10, 2010]]<sup>I</sup> | [[Madison Square Garden]] | Cincinnati | 69 | Louisville | 66\n| February 16, 2011 | Fifth Third Arena | Cincinnati | 63 | No. 16 Louisville | 54\n| February 23, 2012 | Fifth Third Arena | Cincinnati | 60 | No. 17 Louisville | 56\n| [[2012 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|March 10, 2012]] | Madison Square Garden | Cincinnati | 44 | Louisville<sup>\u2020</sup> | 50\n| March 4, 2013 | KFC Yum! Center | Cincinnati | 51 | No. 8 Louisville<sup>\u2020</sup> | 67\n| January 30, 2014 | KFC Yum! Center | No. 13 Cincinnati | 69 | No. 12 Louisville | 66\n| February 22, 2014 | Fifth Third Arena | No. 7 Cincinnati | 57 | No. 11 Louisville<sup>\u2020</sup> | 58\n| note = \u2020 Vacated by Louisville.\n}}\n\n====Notes====\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n<sup>A</sup> [[1959 NCAA University Division Basketball Tournament|1959 NCAA Third Place Game]]<br>\n<sup>B</sup> [[1975 NCAA Division I Basketball Tournament|1975 NCAA Sweet Sixteen]]<br>\n<sup>C</sup> [[Metro Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|1981 Metro Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]]<br>\n<sup>D</sup>[[Metro Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|1984 Metro Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]]<br>\n<sup>E</sup>[[Metro Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|1986 Metro Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]]<br>\n<sup>F</sup> [[1996 Conference USA Men's Basketball Tournament]]<br>\n<sup>G</sup> [[1998 Conference USA Men's Basketball Tournament]]<br>\n<sup>H</sup> [[2004 Conference USA Men's Basketball Tournament]]<br>\n<sup>I</sup> [[2010 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament]]<br>\n<sup>J</sup> [[2012 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament]]<br>\n\n===Wins by location===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#CCCCCC; text-align:center\" | '''Category''' || style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Cincinnati Bearcats}}; text-align:center\" | '''Cincinnati'''|| style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Louisville Cardinals}}; text-align:center\" | '''Louisville'''\n|-\n| align=center | [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, OH]] || align=center | 25 || align=center | 21\n|-\n| align=center | [[Las Cruces, New Mexico|Las Cruces, NM]] || align=center | 0 || align=center | 1\n|-\n| align=center | [[Louisville|Louisville, KY]] || align=center | 16 || align=center | 30\n|-\n| align=center | [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis, TN]] || align=center | 1 || align=center | 1\n|-\n| align=center | [[New York, New York|New York, NY]] || align=center | 1 || align=center | 0\n|}\n\n===Wins by venue===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#CCCCCC; text-align:center\" | '''Category''' || style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Cincinnati Bearcats}}; text-align:center\" | '''Cincinnati'''|| style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Louisville Cardinals}}; text-align:center\" | '''Louisville'''\n|-\n| align=center | Armory Fieldhouse || align=center | 9 || align=center | 2\n|-\n| align=center | Belknap Gymnasium || align=center | 1 || align=center | 0\n|-\n| align=center | Cincinnati Gardens || align=center | 0 || align=center | 2\n|-\n| align=center | Fifth Third Arena || align=center | 11 || align=center | 6\n|-\n| align=center | Freedom Hall || align=center | 14 || align=center | 27\n|-\n| align=center | Heritage Bank Center || align=center | 2 || align=center | 9\n|-\n| align=center | KFC Yum! Center || align=center | 2 || align=center | 0\n|-\n| align=center | Louisville Gardens || align=center | 0 || align=center | 2\n|-\n| align=center | Madison Square Gardens || align=center | 1 || align=center | 0\n|-\n| align=center | Memphis Pyramid || align=center | 1 || align=center | 0\n|-\n| align=center | Mid-South Coliseum || align=center | 0 || align=center | 1\n|-\n| align=center | Pan American Center || align=center | 0 || align=center | 1\n|-\n| align=center | Schmidlapp Gym  || align=center | 3 || align=center | 2\n|}\n\n==Women's Basketball==\n{{See also|Cincinnati Bearcats women's basketball|Louisville Cardinals men's basketball}}\nLouisville leads the all time contest in Women's basketball 41\u201327. Similar to men's basketball and football, the teams have not played since Louisville departed for the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] after the 2013\u201314 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://issuu.com/universityofcincinnatiathletics/docs/2019-20_media_guide_web|title=2019-20 University of Cincinnati Women's Basketball Media Guide|publisher=issuu.com|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Baseball==\n{{See also|Cincinnati Bearcats baseball|Louisville Cardinals baseball}}\nOne of the series that has continued since conference realignment has been games between the baseball teams. The teams have continued to play yearly, with the two having faced off 181 times in their history after first playing in 1924. Louisville leads the series all time, 100\u201381 as of the end of the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gocards.com/news/2019/4/22/baseball-no-6-louisville-hits-road-to-cincinnati-tuesday.aspx|title=No. 6 Louisville Hits Road to Cincinnati Tuesday|publisher=GoCards|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://gobearcats.com/documents/2017/6/14//17_base_guide_2.pdf?id=1191|title=2017 UC Baseball Media Guide|publisher=GoBearcats|accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Cincinnati and Louisville played the first ever [[college baseball]] game at [[Great American Ballpark]], the home of the [[Cincinnati Reds]] on April 6th, 2013. The No. 9 Cardinals would defeat the Bearcats 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gocards.com/news/2013/4/6/No_9_Cardinals_Defeat_Bearcats_in_Reds_Collegiate_Invitational.aspx|title=No. 9 Cardinals Defeat Bearcats in Reds Collegiate Invitational|publisher=GoCards|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2017, the No. 1 Louisville Cardinals played the Cincinnati Bearcats at [[Marge Schott Stadium]]. Cincinnati pulled off an upset, beating Louisville 6\u20133 and handing the Cardinals their first loss of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gobearcats.com/news/2017/3/21/Baseball_Beats_No_1_Louisville_6_3.aspx|title=NBaseball Beats No. 1 Louisville 6-3|publisher=GoBearcats|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cincinnati Bearcats football navbox}}\n{{Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Cincinnati Bearcats women's basketball navbox}}\n{{Cincinnati Bearcats baseball navbox}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals football navbox}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals women's basketball navbox}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals baseball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cincinnati-Louisville rivalry}}\n[[Category:College basketball rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats basketball]]\n[[Category:Louisville Cardinals basketball]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the college sports rivalry|the professional soccer rivalry between FC Cincinnati and Louisville City FC|River Cities Cup}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| wide                  = yes\n| name                  = Cincinnati\u2013Louisville rivalry\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = \n| caption               = \n| team1                 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats]]\n| team1logo             = Cincinnati University Bearcats textlogo.svg\n| team2                 = [[Louisville Cardinals]]\n| team2logo             = Louisville Cardinals wordmark.svg\n| sport                 = [[College football|Football]], [[college basketball|basketball]], others\n| firstmeeting          = 1921\n| mostrecent            = \n| nextmeeting           = \n| total                 = \n| series                = \n| largestvictory        = \n| longeststreak         = \n| longestunbeatenstreak = \n| currentstreak         = \n| currentunbeatenstreak = \n| trophy                = \n| trophy series         = \n| stadiums              =  \n}}\n{{OSM Location map          \n| nolabels = 1    \n| coord = {{coord|38.6|-84.8}}\n| zoom = 7\n| width = 295 \n| height = 250\n| caption = Locations of Cincinnati and Louisville\n| mark1 = Black pog.svg\n| label1 = Cincinnati\n| mark-coord1 = {{coord|39.1329|-84.5150}}\n| label-pos1 = top\n| label-color1 = black\n| mark2 = Red pog.svg\n| label2 = Louisville\n| mark-coord2 = {{coord|38.2527|-85.7585}}\n| label-pos2 = top\n| label-color2 = black\n}}\n\nThe '''Cincinnati\u2013Louisville rivalry''' is a college [[sports rivalry]] between the [[University of Cincinnati]] [[Cincinnati Bearcats|Bearcats]] and the [[University of Louisville]] [[Louisville Cardinals|Cardinals]]. The rivalry between these two schools, located about {{convert|80|mi|km}} apart, dates to their first men's [[college basketball]] game in 1921, and has continued across all sports, with the [[college football|football]] series gaining attention as well, having started in 1929. Both universities share common characteristics, both being over 200 year old institutions in urban settings. The schools have also shared conferences historically, with the rivalry stretching over the span of four conferences from the [[Missouri Valley Conference]], to the [[Metro Conference]] to [[Conference USA]], and more recently in the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Conference]], which in 2013 was renamed to the [[American Athletic Conference]]. After the 2013\u201314 season, Louisville joined the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] and since then the rivalry has been put on hiatus in football and basketball. However, many other sports at the universities, such as baseball, continue to battle periodically. \n\n==History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:88%;\"\n|+ College Comparison\n! \n! style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Cincinnati Bearcats}}\" | [[University of Cincinnati|{{white|Cincinnati}}]]\n! style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Louisville Cardinals}}\" | [[University of Louisville|{{white|Louisville}}]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Founded\n| align=center | 1819 || align=center | 1798\n|-\n! scope=row | Type \n| align=center | [[Public university|Public]] || align=center |[[Public university|Public]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Location\n| align=center |  [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, OH]] || align=center | [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville, KY]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Conference \n| align=center |  [[American Athletic Conference|American]] || align=center | [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Students \n| align=center | 44,338 || align=center | 22,640\n|-\n! scope=row | School colors \n| align=center | {{color box|#E00122}} {{color box|Black}} || align=center | {{color box|#C9001F}} {{color box|Black}}\n|-\n! scope=row | Nickname \n| align=center |  [[Cincinnati Bearcats|Bearcats]] || align=center | [[Louisville Cardinals|Cardinals]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Stadium\n| align=center | [[Nippert Stadium]] || align=center | [[Cardinal Stadium]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Arena\n| align=center | [[Fifth Third Arena]] || align=center | [[KFC Yum! Center]]\n|}\nBoth universities have traced parallel paths, from their early foundation in the early nineteenth century as municipal universities to their later growth into [[University system|state sponsored institutions]] in the 1960s and 70s. Due to their close proximity, the universities became early athletic opponents as college athletics developed first facing off in 1921 in a men's [[college basketball]] game. Additionally, this proximity led to both schools being members of the [[Missouri Valley Conference]], [[Metro Conference]], [[Conference USA]], and the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Conference]] historically. While the rivalry was represented annually in Football from 1966\u20131992 and 1996\u20132013, the true intensity of the rivalry was felt on the basketball court. Legendary coaches [[Denny Crum]], [[Bob Huggins]], and [[Rick Pitino]] each played their part in famous wins for each program and fanning the flames of the matchup. \n\nIn the last year of the rivalry in football and basketball for the foreseeable future, the contests lived up to the pressure. In the battle for [[The Keg of Nails]], [[Teddy Bridgewater]] led the No. 19 Cardinals to an overtime comeback at [[Nippert Stadium]] much to the ire of the Bearcat faithful. On the hardwood both teams would claim upset, ranked wins at their opponent's home court. [[Sean Kilpatrick]] lead the Bearcats to a 69\u201366 victory at the [[KFC Yum! Center]] while [[Russ Smith (basketball)|Russ Smith]] and the Cardinals would beat the Bearcats 58\u201357 at [[Fifth Third Arena]] in their last matchup.\n\n==Football==\n{{Main|The Keg of Nails}}\n{{See also|Cincinnati Bearcats football|Louisville Cardinals football}}\n\n==Men's Basketball==\n{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| wide                  = yes\n| name                  = Cincinnati\u2013Louisville basketball rivalry\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = \n| caption               = \n| team1                 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati Bearcats]]\n| team1logo             = Cincinnati University Bearcats textlogo.svg\n| team2                 = [[Louisville Cardinals men's basketball|Louisville Cardinals]]\n| team2logo             = Louisville Cardinals wordmark.svg\n| sport                 = [[College Basketball]]\n| firstmeeting          = January 17, 1921<br />Cincinnati 36 \u2013 Louisville 16\n| mostrecent            = February 22, 2014<br />Cincinnati 57 \u2013 Louisville 58\n| nextmeeting           = \n| total                 = 99\n| series                = Louisville leads, 53\u201343\n| largestvictory        = \n| longeststreak         = Louisville, 16 (January 19, 1977 \u2013 March 8, 1984)\n| longestunbeatenstreak = \n| currentstreak         = \n| currentunbeatenstreak = \n| trophy                = \n| trophy series         = \n| stadiums              =  \n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:88%;\"\n|+ Men's Basketball Comparison\n! \n! style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Cincinnati Bearcats}}\" | [[University of Cincinnati|{{white|Cincinnati}}]]\n! style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Louisville Cardinals}}\" | [[University of Louisville|{{white|Louisville}}]]\n|-\n! scope=row | First Season\n| align=center | 1901 || align=center | 1911\n|-\n! scope=row | NCAA Championships\n| align=center | 2 || align=center | 3*\n|-\n! scope=row | NCAA Tournament Appearances\n| align=center | 33 || align=center | 43*\n|-\n! scope=row | Conference Championships \n| align=center | 29 || align=center | 23*\n|-\n! scope=row | Conference Tournament Championships\n| align=center | 12 || align=center | 19*\n|-\n! scope=row | All-Americans\n| align=center |  44 || align=center | 25\n|-\n! scope=row | Consensus 1st Team All-Americans\n| align=center | 8 || align=center | 7\n|-\n! scope=row | Player of the Year\n| align=center | 3 || align=center | 1\n|-\n! scope=row | Conference Player of the Year\n| align=center | 10 || align=center | 10\n|}\n{{See also|Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Louisville Cardinals men's basketball}}\n[[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati]] and [[Louisville Cardinals men's basketball|Louisville]] were rivals, first playing in 1921, until the [[2010\u201314 NCAA conference realignment]] put the contest on hiatus, as Louisville moved to the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] on July 1, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/8685541/acc-votes-add-louisville-cardinals|title=ACC votes to add Louisville in 2014|accessdate=19 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312052203/http://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/8685541/acc-votes-add-louisville-cardinals|archivedate=12 March 2017}}</ref> The teams have faced off 99 times in basketball series history, with Louisville leading the all-time series 53\u201343.<ref name=\"Media Guide\">{{cite news|url=https://gobearcats.com/documents/2018/10/19/2018_19_Cincinnati_MBB_Media_Guide.pdf|title=UC Basketball Media Guide|publisher=GoBearcats|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Bearcats and Cardinals have played in eight conference tournaments, with the Bearcats and Cardinals tied at 4\u20134. Louisville won all 3 games in the [[Metro Conference]] with Cincinnati winning all 3 games in [[Conference USA]]. The teams split 1\u20131 in the [[Big East (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] tournament. \n\nThe teams have also met twice in the NCAA Tournament, tied overall at 1\u20131.\n\n===Notable Games===\n'''March 21, 1959''': The Bearcats met the Cardinals on their home court, [[Freedom Hall]], for the Third Place game of the [[1959 NCAA University Division Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]. [[Oscar Robertson]] would score 39 points, earning the first [[triple double]] in Final Four history, leading his Bearcats to a 98\u201385 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/amp/Sports/story?id=4444058&page=1|title=Unforgettable March Madness Moments|author=|publisher=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''March 20, 1975''': The No. 3 Cardinals collided with the No. 12 Bearcats in the Sweet Sixteen of the [[1975 NCAA Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]. Louisville took a solid lead in the first half which proved too much for the Bearcats to overcome, seeing the Cardinals win 78\u201363. Louisville would go on to finish 3rd overall in the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/boxscores/1975-03-20-cincinnati.html|title=Louisville vs. Cincinnati Box Score, March 20, 1975|author=|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''March 8, 1981''': The reigning National Champion Cardinals took on the Bearcats in the final of the [[Metro Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Metro Conference Tournament]] at Freedom Hall. In an ugly, low scoring affair the Cardinals were triumphant in the game to a score of 42\u201331.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/louisville/2014/11/26/upon-review-louisville-basketball-savannah-state-rout/19522031/|title=The history behind U of L's rout on Monday|author=Jeff Greer|publisher=[[Louisville Courier Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n'''March 8, 1996''': In 1991 Cincinnati left the Metro Conference to form the [[Great Midwest Conference]], putting the rivalry on a five-year hiatus. In 1995, the Great Midwest and Metro combined to form [[Conference USA]] bringing the Bearcats and Cardinals back into the same conference. No. 21 Louisville took the first game 72\u201366 at the [[Fifth Third Arena|Shoemaker Center]] in February, but with revenge on their mind the [[Bob Huggins]] lead No. 8 Bearcats defeated No. 22 Louisville in the [[1996 Conference USA Men's Basketball Tournament|Conference Tournament]] Quarterfinals 92\u201381. In the [[1996 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]] the Bearcats advanced to the Elite Eight and the Cardinals made it to the Sweet Sixteen.\n\n'''February 22, 2003''': No. 4 Louisville traveled to Cincinnati and were stunned by the 31 point performance of Leonard Stokes that would help navigate the Bearcats to the 101\u201380 upset of the Cardinals. The Bearcats would also set a school record, shooting 42-of-58 on free throws in the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=230532132|title=Pitino ejected in second half of Cardinals' loss|author=|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''March 11, 2004''': Cincinnati and Louisville faced off in the [[2004 Conference USA Men's Basketball Tournament]] hosted at [[Heritage Bank Center|US Bank Arena]] in Cincinnati. After splitting the regular season matchups, the Bearcats proved too much for [[Rick Pitino]]'s Cardinals winning 64\u201362 after Armein Kirkland banked a shot in for the Bearcats with only 16.9 seconds remaining. The No. 13 Bearcats would go on to win the conference tournament. This game was Huggins's last victory in the matchup.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=240712132|title=Kirkland scores with 16.9 seconds left|author=|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''March 10, 2012'''\u2020: In an unlikely [[2012 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|Big East Tournament]] championship game, Louisville and Cincinnati faced off, with [[Mick Cronin (basketball)|Mick Cronin]] coaching against his former boss Pitino. Cincinnati fought their way past No. 13 [[2011\u201312 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|Georgetown]] in double overtime and No. 2 [[2011\u201312 Syracuse Orange men's basketball team|Syracuse]] while Louisville beat No. 9 [[2011\u201312 Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball team|Marquette]] and No. 23 [[2011\u201312 Notre Dame Fighting Irish men's basketball team|Notre Dame]]. Louisville ended up winning the tilt 50\u201344, in what was the lowest scoring championship game in Big East history. Both teams made runs in the [[2012 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]] with Cincinnati advancing to the Sweet Sixteen and Louisville making it to the Final Four.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=320702132|title=Louisville edges Cincinnati to win Big East tournament for 2nd time|author=|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''February 22, 2014'''\u2020: In the last matchup between rivals before Louisville left for the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] the teams met at [[Fifth Third Arena]]. No. 7 Cincinnati and No. 11 Louisville played in a memorable, blow-for-blow game which would see [[Sean Kilpatrick]] record 28 points. However, in the dwindling seconds of the second half, [[Russ Smith (basketball)|Russ Smith]] scored with 3 seconds remaining, earning Louisville a 58\u201357 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400497012|title=Russ Smith's jumper in final seconds helps Louisville upend Cincy|author=|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\u2020 Denotes game vacated by Louisville\n\n===Game results===\nRankings are from the [[AP Poll]] (1936\u2013present)\n\n{{sports rivalry series table\n| legend_forfeit_text = Vacated wins{{#tag:ref|Louisville has vacated all of its victories from the 2011\u201312, 2012\u201313, 2013\u201314, 2014\u201315 seasons. These 123 wins are not included in Louisville's all-time record, nor are the victories against Cincinnati during this span counted in the series record between the two teams.<ref name=\"Sanctions\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/02/20/louisville-basketball-will-vacate-2013-national-championship-as-ncaa-upholds-ruling/]. [[Washington Post]], 2018-02-20.</ref>|group=\"n\"|name=\"vacation\"}}\n| format = compact| cols = 2\n| team1 = Cincinnati\n| team1style = {{NCAA secondary color cell|Cincinnati Bearcats}}\n| team2 = Louisville\n| team2style = {{NCAA color cell|Louisville Cardinals}}\n| series_summary = yes\n\n| January 17, 1921 | Schmidlapp Gym | Cincinnati | 36 | Louisville | 16\n| December 20, 1924 | Schmidlapp Gym | Cincinnati | 29 | Louisville | 18\n| December 21, 1938 | Belknap Gymnasium | Cincinnati | 54 | Louisville | 41\n| December 21, 1939 | Schmidlapp Gym | Cincinnati | 62 | Louisville | 17\n| January 12, 1946 | [[Louisville Gardens]] | Cincinnati | 40 | Louisville | 59\n| January 22, 1946 | Schmidlapp Gym | Cincinnati | 39 | Lou