i, Nahnu Abna'u Wa Ahfadu Rijalik\n:Sawfa Nahmi Kulla Ma Bayna Yadayna Min Jalalik.\n:Wa Sayabqa Khalida 'D-daw'i 'Ala Kulli 'El-masalik\n:Kullu Sakhrin Fi Jibalik, Kullu Dharrati Rimalik.\n\n:II:\n:Kullu Anda'i Dilalik, Milkuna\n:Innaha Milku Amanina 'L-kabirah, Haqqana\n:Ja'a Min Amjadi Madiki 'L-muthirah.\n\n:Raddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi\n:Raddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi\n\n:Chorus:\n\n:III:\n:Wahdati, Wahdati, Ya Nashidan Ra'i'an Yamla'u Nafsi\n:Anti Ahdun 'Aliqun Fi Kulli Dhimmah.\n:Rayati, Rayati, Ya Nasijan Hiktahu Min Kulli Shamsi\n:Ukhludi Khafiqatan Fi Kulli Qimmah.\n:Ummati, Ummati, Imnahini 'L-ba'sa Ya Masdari Ba'si\n:Wa 'Dhkhurini Laki Ya Akrama Ummah.\n\n:IV:\n:'Ishtu Imani Wa Hubbi Sarmadiyya\n:Wa Masiri Fawqa Darbi 'Arabiyya.\n:'Ishtu Imani Wa Hubbi Sarmadiyya\n:Wa Masiri Fawqa Darbi 'Arabiyya.\n:Wa Sayabqa Nabdu Qalbi Yamaniyya\n:Lan Tara 'D-dunya Ala Ardi Wasiyya.\n\n:Chorus:\n|\n:Chorus:\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n:Echo it over and over again.\n:Remember, through my joy, each martyr.\n:Clothe him with the shining mantles off our festivals.\n\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n\n:Verse 1\n:Oh my country, we are children and grandchildren of your men.\n:We will guard all of your majesty in our hands.\n:Its light will remain for ever, in every place.\n:Every rock of your mountains, and every particle of your soil.\n\n:Verse 2\n:All the moisture of your waters, are ours.\n:It is the sovereign of our hopes, and our right.\n:The come from the great glories of your past.\n\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n\n:Chorus:\n\n:Verse 3\n:My unity, Oh marvelous song which fills my heart,\n:You are the promise of all to come, \n:My banner, Oh cloth nailed from every sun\n:Raised forever, on every peak\n:My nation, give me strength, Oh source of strength\n:And save me for you, the best of nations.\n\n:Verse 4\n:In faith and love I am part of mankind,\n:And I shall march first among the Arabs.\n:And my heart beat shall remain that of a Yemenite.\n:No foreigner shall ever hold dominion over Yemen.\n\n:Chorus:\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nationalanthems.me/yemen-united-republic/ Yemen: ''United Republic'' - Audio of the national anthem of Yemen, with information and lyrics]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/olmedia/780000/audio/_784383_yemen.ram Instrumental version of \"United Republic\" in RealAudio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061107170930/http://www.yemenembassy.org/images/anthem1.bmp Lyrics in Arabic]\n* [http://www.szbszig.atw.hu/yemen.htm Himnuszok] - A vocal version of the Anthem, featured in \"Himnuszok\" website.\n\n{{Nationalanthemsofasia}}\n\n[[Category:Yemeni songs]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Yemen]]\n[[Category:Asian anthems|Yemen]]\n[[Category:National anthem compositions in C major]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox anthem\n|title         = {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0645\u0647\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u062d\u062f\u0629}}\n|transcription = ''al-Jumh\u016br\u012byah al-Mutta\u1e25id\u00e2h''\n|english_title = United Republic\n|image         = \n|image_size    =\n|caption       =\n|prefix        = National\n|country       = {{YEM}}\n----\nFormer national anthem of {{flag|South Yemen|1979-1990}}\n|author        = Abdullah \"Al-Fadhool\" Abdulwahab Noman\n|lyrics_date   =\n|composer      = [[Ayoob Tarish]]\n|music_date    =\n|adopted       = 22 May 1990\n|until         =\n|sound         = United States Navy Band - United Republic.ogg\n|sound_title   = United Republic (Instrumental)\n}}\n'''United Republic''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0645\u0647\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u062d\u062f\u0629}}; ''al-Jumh\u016br\u012byah al-Mutta\u1e25id\u00e2h''), is the [[national anthem]] of [[Yemen]]. It was written by Abdullah \"Al-Fadhool\" Abdulwahab Noman and composed by [[Ayoob Tarish]]. The music was formerly the anthem of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen ([[South Yemen]]) but it became the anthem of the whole country when both sides merged in 1990.\nDuring the South Yemen period, the title was ('Arabic: '''\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0637\u0646\u064a \u0644\u062c\u0645\u0647\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u064a\u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0645\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0637\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0628\u064a\u0629''', 'n-Nash\u012bd Al-Wa\u1e6dani Le-Jemh\u016br\u012byyat 'l-yaman 'D-demuqr\u0101\u1e6diyya.)<ref>{{cite web|title=Yemen National Anthem|url=http://www.nationalanthems.info/ye.htm|publisher=National Anthems.info}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\n\n===Official lyrics, used by the [[Republic of Yemen]] ( 2006 - Present )===\n{| cellpadding=6\n![[Arabic language|Arabic]] lyrics \n!Transliteration\n!English translation\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n| style=\"direction:rtl;\" |\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a \u0623\u064a\u062a\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a\u0647 \u0648\u0623\u0639\u064a\u062f\u064a \u0648\u0623\u0639\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n\u0648\u0627\u0630\u0643\u0631\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0641\u0631\u062d\u062a\u064a \u0643\u0644 \u0634\u0647\u064a\u062f<br />\n\u0648\u0623\u0645\u0646\u062d\u064a\u0647 \u062d\u0644\u0644\u0627\u064b \u0645\u0646 \u0636\u0648\u0621 \u0639\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n<br />\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a \u0623\u064a\u062a\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a \u0623\u064a\u062a\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n<br />\n\u0648\u062d\u062f\u062a\u064a..\u0648\u062d\u062f\u062a\u064a..\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u0627\u064b \u0631\u0627\u0626\u0639\u0627\u064b \u064a\u0645\u0644\u0627\u064f \u0646\u0641\u0633\u064a<br />\n\u0623\u0646\u062a \u0639\u0647\u062f \u0639\u0627\u0644\u0642 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0644 \u0630\u0645\u0629<br />\n\u0631\u0627\u064a\u062a\u064a.. \u0631\u0627\u064a\u062a\u064a..\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0633\u064a\u062c\u0627\u064b \u062d\u0643\u062a\u0647 \u0645\u0646 \u0643\u0644 \u0634\u0645\u0633<br />\n\u0623\u062e\u0644\u062f\u064a \u062e\u0627\u0641\u0642\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0644 \u0642\u0645\u0629<br />\n\u0623\u0645\u062a\u064a.. \u0623\u0645\u062a\u064a.. \u0627\u0645\u0646\u062d\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0623\u0633 \u064a\u0627\u0645\u0635\u062f\u0631 \u0628\u0623\u0633\u064a<br />\n\u0648\u0623\u0630\u062e\u0631\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0644\u0643 \u064a\u0627 \u0623\u0643\u0631\u0645 \u0623\u0645\u0629<br />\n<br />\n\u0639\u0634\u062a \u0625\u064a\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0648\u062d\u0628\u064a \u0623\u0645\u0645\u064a\u0627<br />\n\u0648\u0645\u0633\u064a\u0631\u064a \u0641\u0648\u0642 \u062f\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0627<br />\n\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0628\u0642\u0649 \u0646\u0628\u0636 \u0642\u0644\u0628\u064a \u064a\u0645\u0646\u064a\u0627<br />\n\u0644\u0646 \u062a\u0631\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0623\u0631\u0636\u064a \u0648\u0635\u064a\u0627<br />\n|\nRaddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi<br/>\nRaddidihi Wa-a 'idi Wa-a idi<br/>\nWa 'Dhkuri Fi Farhati Kulla Shahidi<br/>\nWa'Mnahihi Hullalan Min Daw'i Idi<br/>\n<br/>\nRaddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi<br/>\nRaddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi<br/>\n<br/>\nWahdati, Wahdati, Ya Nashidan Ra'i'an Yamla'u Nafsi<br/>\nAnti Ahdun 'Aliqun Fi Kulli Dhimmah<br/>\nRayati, Rayati, Ya Nasijan Hiktahu Min Kulli Shamsi<br/>\nUkhludi Khafiqatan Fi Kulli Qimmah<br/>\nUmmati, Ummati, Imnahini 'L-ba'sa Ya Masdari Ba'si<br/>\nWa 'Dhkhurini Laki Ya Akrama Ummah<br/>\n<br/>\n'Ishtu Imani Wa Hubbi o'omamia <br/>\nWa-masiri Fawqa Darbi Arabiyya<br/>\nWa-sayabqa Nabdu Qalbi Yamaniyya<br/>\nLan Tara 'D-dunya Ala Ardi Wasiyya.<br/>\n|\n: Repeat, O World, my song.\n: Echo it over and over again.\n: Remember, through my joy, each martyr.\n: Clothe him with the shining mantles of our festivals.\n\n: Repeat, O World, my song.\n\n:My unity, Oh marvelous song which fills my heart,\n:You are the promise of all to come, \n:My banner, Oh cloth nailed from every sun\n:Raised forever, on every peak\n:My nation, give me strength, Oh source of strength\n:And save me for you, the best of nations.\n\n:In faith and love I am part of mankind,\n:And I shall march first among the Arabs.\n:And my heart beat shall remain that of a Yemenite.\n:No foreigner shall ever hold dominion over Yemen.\n|}\n\n===Original lyrics, used by the [[Yemen|Republic of Yemen]] ( 1990 - 2006 ) ===\n{| cellpadding=6\n![[Arabic language|Arabic]] lyrics \n!Transliteration\n!English translation\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n| style=\"direction:rtl;\" |\nChorus:<br/>\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a \u0623\u064a\u062a\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a\u0647 \u0648\u0623\u0639\u064a\u062f\u064a \u0648\u0623\u0639\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n\u0648\u0627\u0630\u0643\u0631\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0641\u0631\u062d\u062a\u064a \u0643\u0644 \u0634\u0647\u064a\u062f<br />\n\u0648\u0623\u0645\u0646\u062d\u064a\u0647 \u062d\u0644\u0644\u0627\u064b \u0645\u0646 \u0636\u0648\u0621 \u0639\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n<br />\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a \u0623\u064a\u062a\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u064a<br />\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a \u0623\u064a\u062a\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u064a\n\n1<br/>\n\u064a\u0640\u0627 \u0628\u0644\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0646\u062d\u0646 \u0623\u0628\u0646\u0640\u0627\u0621 \u0648\u0623\u062d\u0641\u0627\u062f \u0631\u062c\u0627\u0644\u0643<br/>\n\u0633\u0648\u0641 \u0646\u062d\u0645\u064a \u0643\u0644 \u0645\u0627 \u0628\u064a\u0646 \u064a\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0627 \u0645\u0646 \u062c\u0644\u0627\u0644\u0640\u0643<br/>\n\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0628\u0642\u0649 \u062e\u0627\u0644\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0636\u0648\u0621 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0643\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u0627\u0644\u0643<br/>\n\u0643\u0644 \u0635\u062e\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u062c\u0628\u0627\u0644\u0643 ..<br/>\n\u0643\u0644 \u0630\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0631\u0645\u0627\u0644\u0643\n\n2<br/>\n\u0643\u0640\u0644 \u0623\u0646\u062f\u0627\u0621\u0641\u064a \u0636\u0640\u0644\u0627\u0644\u0640\u0643 ..<br/>\n\u0645\u0640\u0644\u0640\u0643\u0646\u0627<br/>\n\u0625\u0646\u0640\u0647\u0627 \u0645\u0644\u0643 \u0623\u0645\u0640\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0640\u0643\u0628\u064a\u0631\u0629..<br/>\n\u062d\u0642\u0646\u0627 \u062c\u0627\u0621 \u0645\u0646 \u0623\u0645\u062c\u0627\u062f \u0645\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062b\u064a\u0631\u0629\n\nChorus:\n\n3<br/>\n\u0648\u062d\u062f\u062a\u064a .. \u0648\u062d\u062f\u062a\u064a ..<br/>\n\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u0627 \u0631\u0627\u0626\u0640\u0639\u0627\u064b \u064a\u0645\u0644\u0623 \u0646\u0640\u0641\u0633\u064a \u0623\u0646\u062a\u0650 \u0639\u0640\u0647\u062f \u0639\u0627\u0644\u0642 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0644 \u0630\u0645\u0629<br/>\n\u0631\u0627\u064a\u062a\u064a .. \u0631\u0627\u064a\u062a\u064a ..<br/>\n\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0633\u064a\u062c\u0627\u064b \u062d\u0643\u062a\u0647 \u0645\u0646 \u0643\u0644 \u0634\u0640\u0645\u0633 \u0627\u062e\u0640\u0644\u062f\u064a \u062e\u0627\u0641\u0642\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0644 \u0642\u0645\u0629<br/>\n\u0623\u0645\u062a\u064a .. \u0623\u0645\u062a\u064a ..<br/>\n\u0627\u0645\u0646\u062d\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0623\u0633 \u064a\u0627 \u0645\u0635\u062f\u0631 \u0628\u0623\u0633\u064a \u0648\u0627\u0630\u062e\u0631\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0644\u0643 \u064a\u0627 \u0623\u0643\u0631\u0645 \u0623\u0645\u0629\n\n4<br/>\n\u0639\u0634\u062a \u0625\u064a\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0648\u062d\u0628\u064a \u0633\u0631\u0645\u062f\u064a\u0627 <br/>\n\u0648\u0645\u0633\u064a\u0631\u064a \u0641\u0648\u0642 \u062f\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0627<br/>\n\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0628\u0642\u0649 \u0646\u0628\u0640\u0636 \u0642\u0644\u0628\u064a \u064a\u0645\u0646\u064a\u0627<br/>\n\u0644\u0646 \u062a\u0631\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0623\u0631\u0636\u064a \u0648\u0635\u064a\u0627<br/>\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a \u0623\u064a\u062a\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u064a<br/>\n\u0631\u062f\u062f\u064a \u0623\u064a\u062a\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0646\u0634\u064a\u062f\u064a\n\nChorus:<br/>\n|\n:Chorus:\n:Raddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi\n:Raddidihi Wa a'idi Wa aidi.\n:Wa 'Dhkuri Fi Farhati Kulla Shahidi\n:Wa 'Mnahihi Hullalan Min Daw'i Idi.\n\n:Raddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi\n:Raddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi.\n\n:I:\n:Ya Biladi, Nahnu Abna'u Wa Ahfadu Rijalik\n:Sawfa Nahmi Kulla Ma Bayna Yadayna Min Jalalik.\n:Wa Sayabqa Khalida 'D-daw'i 'Ala Kulli 'El-masalik\n:Kullu Sakhrin Fi Jibalik, Kullu Dharrati Rimalik.\n\n:II:\n:Kullu Anda'i Dilalik, Milkuna\n:Innaha Milku Amanina 'L-kabirah, Haqqana\n:Ja'a Min Amjadi Madiki 'L-muthirah.\n\n:Raddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi\n:Raddidi Ayyatuha 'D-dunya Nashidi\n\n:Chorus:\n\n:III:\n:Wahdati, Wahdati, Ya Nashidan Ra'i'an Yamla'u Nafsi\n:Anti Ahdun 'Aliqun Fi Kulli Dhimmah.\n:Rayati, Rayati, Ya Nasijan Hiktahu Min Kulli Shamsi\n:Ukhludi Khafiqatan Fi Kulli Qimmah.\n:Ummati, Ummati, Imnahini 'L-ba'sa Ya Masdari Ba'si\n:Wa 'Dhkhurini Laki Ya Akrama Ummah.\n\n:IV:\n:'Ishtu Imani Wa Hubbi Sarmadiyya\n:Wa Masiri Fawqa Darbi 'Arabiyya.\n:'Ishtu Imani Wa Hubbi Sarmadiyya\n:Wa Masiri Fawqa Darbi 'Arabiyya.\n:Wa Sayabqa Nabdu Qalbi Yamaniyya\n:Lan Tara 'D-dunya Ala Ardi Wasiyya.\n\n:Chorus:\n|\n:Chorus:\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n:Echo it over and over again.\n:Remember, through my joy, each martyr.\n:Clothe him with the shining mantles off our festivals.\n\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n\n:Verse 1\n:Oh my country, we are children and grandchildren of your men.\n:We will guard all of your majesty in our hands.\n:Its light will remain for ever, in every place.\n:Every rock of your mountains, and every particle of your soil.\n\n:Verse 2\n:All the moisture of your waters, are ours.\n:It is the sovereign of our hopes, and our right.\n:The come from the great glories of your past.\n\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n:Repeat, Oh World, my song.\n\n:Chorus:\n\n:Verse 3\n:My unity, Oh marvelous song which fills my heart,\n:You are the promise of all to come, \n:My banner, Oh cloth nailed from every sun\n:Raised forever, on every peak\n:My nation, give me strength, Oh source of strength\n:And save me for you, the best of nations.\n\n:Verse 4\n:In faith and love I am part of mankind,\n:And I shall march first among the Arabs.\n:And my heart beat shall remain that of a Yemenite.\n:No foreigner shall ever hold dominion over Yemen.\n\n:Chorus:\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nationalanthems.me/yemen-united-republic/ Yemen: ''United Republic'' - Audio of the national anthem of Yemen, with information and lyrics]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/olmedia/780000/audio/_784383_yemen.ram Instrumental version of \"United Republic\" in RealAudio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061107170930/http://www.yemenembassy.org/images/anthem1.bmp Lyrics in Arabic]\n* [http://www.szbszig.atw.hu/yemen.htm Himnuszok] - A vocal version of the Anthem, featured in \"Himnuszok\" website.\n\n{{Nationalanthemsofasia}}\n\n[[Category:Yemeni songs]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Yemen]]\n[[Category:Asian anthems|Yemen]]\n[[Category:National anthem compositions in C major]]\n", "name_user": "Illegitimate Barrister", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_anthem_of_Yemen"}
{"title_page": "The Shame of Life", "text_new": "{{More references|date=February 2007}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Shame of Life\n| cover      = The Shame of Life (Butthole Surfers single - cover art).jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Butthole Surfers]]\n| album      = [[Weird Revolution]]\n| released   = 2001\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]], [[rap rock]]\n| length     = 3:30\n| label      = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n| writer     = [[Kid Rock|Robert J. Ritchie]], [[Gibby Haynes]], [[Paul Leary]], [[King Coffey]]\n| producer   = [[Rob Cavallo]], [[Paul Leary]]\n| prev_title = [[Jingle of a Dog's Collar]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Dracula from Houston]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}\n\n\"'''The Shame of Life'''\" is a song by [[United States|American]] [[alternative rock]] band [[Butthole Surfers]], from their 2001 album ''[[Weird Revolution]]''. The song was released as a [[CD single]] in [[Australia]] and peaked at #24 on [[Billboard charts|Billboard]]'s [[Modern Rock Tracks]]. The chorus was written by rapper [[Kid Rock]], who retains a songwriting credit for the track.<ref>https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/all-grown-up-2/</ref>\n\nIt reached number 93 in [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2001|Triple J's Hottest 100 of 2001]].\n\nA music video was made for the song, featuring the band going to a bizarre house party that is portrayed by the lyrics sung by Gibby Haynes (e.g. \"there were squirrels smoking crack\" as a prop squirrel is shown smoking the drug). Throughout the video, other weird and disturbing events take place such as pigs with \"Get Down\" painted on their bodies, hot women dancing, anthropomorphic squirrels in suits that attack and drug the band, a man wearing a pig mask, Haynes wearing a modified glove with what appear to be hypodermic needles, a lady wearing a dress made of dollar bills, a man swinging a shovel around, and some women with their faces resembling squirrels. The video ends with Haynes being dragged outside by two of the anthropomorphic squirrels.\n\nThe song was featured in a trailer for the 2002 film ''[[Phone Booth (film)|Phone Booth]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"The Shame of Life\" \u2013 3:30\n#\"The Shame of Life\" (A Cappella) \u2013 3:30\n#\"The Shame of Life\" ([[DJ Z-Trip]] Remix) \u2013 4:15\n#\"The Shame of Life\" (Bonus Beats) \u2013 3:49\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{ButtholeSurfers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shame Of Life, The}}\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:Butthole Surfers songs]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records singles]]\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kid Rock]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Rob Cavallo]]\n\n\n{{2000s-rock-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Shame of Life\n| cover      = The Shame of Life (Butthole Surfers single - cover art).jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Butthole Surfers]]\n| album      = [[Weird Revolution]]\n| released   = 2001\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]], [[rap rock]]\n| length     = 3:30\n| label      = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n| writer     = [[Kid Rock|Robert J. Ritchie]], [[Gibby Haynes]], [[Paul Leary]], [[King Coffey]]\n| producer   = [[Rob Cavallo]], [[Paul Leary]]\n| prev_title = [[Jingle of a Dog's Collar]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Dracula from Houston]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}\n\n\"'''The Shame of Life'''\" is a song by [[United States|American]] [[alternative rock]] band [[Butthole Surfers]], from their 2001 album ''[[Weird Revolution]]''. The song was released as a [[CD single]] in [[Australia]] and peaked at #24 on [[Billboard charts|Billboard]]'s [[Modern Rock Tracks]]. The chorus was written by rapper [[Kid Rock]], who retains a songwriting credit for the track. <ref>https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/all-grown-up-2/</ref>\n\nIt reached number 93 in [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2001|Triple J's Hottest 100 of 2001]].\n\nA music video was made for the song, featuring the band going to a bizarre house party that is portrayed by the lyrics sung by Gibby Haynes (e.g. \"there were squirrels smoking crack\" as a prop squirrel is shown smoking the drug). Throughout the video, other weird and disturbing events take place such as pigs with \"Get Down\" painted on their bodies, hot women dancing, anthropomorphic squirrels in suits that attack and drug the band, a man wearing a pig mask, Haynes wearing a modified glove with what appear to be hypodermic needles, a lady wearing a dress made of dollar bills, a man swinging a shovel around, and some women with their faces resembling squirrels. The video ends with Haynes being dragged outside by two of the anthropomorphic squirrels.\n\nThe song was featured in a trailer for the 2002 film ''[[Phone Booth (film)|Phone Booth]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"The Shame of Life\" \u2013 3:30\n#\"The Shame of Life\" (A Cappella) \u2013 3:30\n#\"The Shame of Life\" ([[DJ Z-Trip]] Remix) \u2013 4:15\n#\"The Shame of Life\" (Bonus Beats) \u2013 3:49\n\n{{ButtholeSurfers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shame Of Life, The}}\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:Butthole Surfers songs]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records singles]]\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kid Rock]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Rob Cavallo]]\n\n\n{{2000s-rock-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Shame_of_Life"}
{"title_page": "Michael Frimkess", "text_new": "{{short description|American ceramic artist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Michael Frimkess\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       =\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1937|01|08}}\n| birth_place   = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| residence     = [[Venice, California]]\n| education     = [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in [[Ceramics]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Otis College of Art and Design]]\n| nationality   =\n| other_names   =\n| occupation    = [[Ceramist]]\n| years_active  = 1955\u2013present\n| spouse        = Magdalena Suarez Frimkess\n| known_for     =\n| movement      = [[California Clay Movement]]\n| notable_works =\n}}\n\n'''Michael Frimkess''' (born January 8, 1937) is an American [[ceramic art]]ist who lives in [[Venice, California]]. In the 1950s and 60s, he was a pupil of [[Peter Voulkos]], a prominent figure in the [[California Clay Movement]]. Frimkess' [[pottery]] is noted for its classical style, employing forms from [[Pottery of ancient Greece|Greek]], [[Chinese ceramics|Chinese]], and [[Ceramics of indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous American]] antiquity. His wife and collaborator, Magdalena Suarez Frimkess, paints his ceramic pieces often using anachronistic, contemporary images like [[Minnie Mouse]] or [[Condorito]]. He is also well-known for his innovative wheel-throwing and firing techniques.\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrimkess was born on January 8, 1937<ref name=\"AAA\">{{cite news | last=Karlstrom| first=Paul| title =Oral history interview with Michael and Magdalena Suarez Frimkess, 2001 March 8-April 17| newspaper =| publisher =Archives of American Art| date =March 8, 2001 | url =https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-michael-and-magdalena-suarez-frimkess-13128#transcript| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> in [[Eastside Los Angeles|East]] [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]. He grew up largely in the neighborhood of [[Boyle Heights, Los Angeles|Boyle Heights]]<ref name=\"LAT2000\">{{cite news | last=Muchnic| first=Suzanne| title =Their Lives Poured Into Clay| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =November 19, 2000 | url =http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/19/entertainment/ca-54053| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> and claimed to have been among one of the last Jewish families in the area.<ref name=\"AmerPotters\">{{cite book |last=Clark |first=Garth |date=January 1, 1981 |title=American Potters: The Work of 20 Modern Masters |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q2NQAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjutMvp27bdAhUCqVQKHQ39Ax44ChDoAQgxMAI |location= |publisher=Watson-Guptill |page=41 |isbn=978-0823002139 |author-link=Garth Clark }}</ref> His father, Lou Frimkess, was an artist and graphic designer.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"LATLou\">{{cite news | last=Fitzgerald| first=Patrick| title =Landmark Designer| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =November 26, 2000 | url =http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/26/entertainment/ca-57261| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> He was exposed to fine art early in his childhood, receiving drawing and sculpting lessons, and being taken to numerous museum exhibitions. Frimkess learned how to play the [[saxophone]] and [[piano]] in his youth and aspired to become a jazz musician.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"Hammer2014\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Magdalena Suarez Frimkess & Michael Frimkess| newspaper =| publisher =Hammer Museum| date =2014 | url =https://hammer.ucla.edu/made-in-la-2014/magdalena-suarez-frimkess-michael-frimkess/| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> At age 15, his family moved to [[Hollywood]] and he would graduate from [[Hollywood High School]] two years later in 1955. In high school, he took up sculpture, which led him to seek out art schools after graduation. At the age of 17 he became the youngest person to receive a scholarship from the [[Otis College of Art and Design]] (then known as the Los Angeles County Art Institute).<ref name=\"AAA\"/><ref name=\"LAT2000\"/>\n \nAfter a year at the college, Frimkess switched his focus to ceramics, a move that he attributes to a [[peyote]]-induced vision of himself throwing a perfectly-shaped vessel.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"ClayToday\">{{cite book |last=Drexler Lynn |first=Martha |date=June 1, 1990 |title=Clay Today: Contemporary Ceramists and Their Work |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QVpQAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjutMvp27bdAhUCqVQKHQ39Ax44ChDoAQhEMAY |location= |publisher=Chronicle Books |page=68 |isbn=978-0877017561 |author-link= }}</ref> In the ceramics department, he studied under Peter Voulkos, perhaps the most notable figure in the California Clay Movement.<ref name=\"Intro\">{{cite news | last=Bartolucci| first=Marisa| title =A New Focus on Mid-Century Ceramist Peter Voulkos| newspaper =| publisher =Introspective| date = January 30, 2017| url =https://www.1stdibs.com/introspective-magazine/peter-voulkos/| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> He also worked alongside sculptors and ceramists like [[Billy Al Bengston]], [[John Mason (artist)|John Mason]], [[Kenneth Price]], [[Paul Soldner]], and others.<ref name=\"ClayToday\"/> In 1956, he was one of 10 young artists to open and display work at a gallery on [[Sunset Boulevard]].<ref name=\"LAT1956\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =In The Galleries - Young Artists| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =June 24, 1956 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/380998990/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 1957, Frimkess worked in a small ceramics factory while on a trip with his family in [[Italy]], where he received additional training in throwing a very hard type of clay.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/>\n \n==Career==\n[[File:Michael Frimkess, Magdalena Suarez Frimkess, Blues for Dr. Banks -Miles Davis-, 1972-74 (11501307495).jpg|thumb|''Blues for Dr. Banks'' by Michael and Magdalena Frimkess]]\nIn the early 1960s, Frimkess went to [[Berkeley, California]] where [[Peter Voulkos]] was then teaching at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. While there, he studied bronze and aluminum casting with Voulkos.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/> In 1963, his piece \"Hooker No. 1\" (a bronze sculpture of a television) was displayed at the [[San Francisco Art Institute]]'s Annual exhibition at the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]].<ref name=\"SFE1963\">{{cite news | last=Fried| first=Alexander| title =The Annual: Raw, Rough and Not a Lyrical Note| newspaper =The San Francisco Examiner| publisher =| date =March 31, 1963 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/458553664/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> Also that year at the behest of Voulkos, Frimkess took an internship at the Clay Art Center in [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. It was there that he met his future wife and frequent collaborator, Magdalena Suarez, who had come to the Art Center from [[Venezuela]] as part of a fellowship program.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/> While on the east coast, Frimkess was instructed to visit museums in [[New York City|New York]] and [[Boston]] to study Greek and Chinese forms of pottery. He also began learning the technique of \"dry throwing\" clay rather than using water.<ref name=\"ClayToday\"/><ref name=\"HistAmerCer\">{{cite book |last=Levin |first=Elaine |date=October 6, 1988 |title=The History of American Ceramics: From Pipkins and Bean Pots to Contemporary Forms |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=unpQAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijt-et47bdAhUQKHwKHWIJA0U4ChDoAQhJMAc |location= |publisher=Harry N. Abrams |page=232 |isbn=978-0810911727 |author-link= }}</ref> Much of his work after 1965 replicated classical forms like Greek volute [[kraters]], [[Zuni]] pots, and Chinese ginger jars.<ref name=\"AmerPotters\"/><ref name=\"CerArtPerc\">{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CfVUAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjl9tHt5LbdAhWT7Z8KHVUmCgw4FBDoAQg7MAQ |title=Ceramics, Art and Perception, Issues 47-50|publisher=Ceramics, Art and Perception |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn 1966, his work was featured in the ''Abstract Expressionist Ceramics'' exhibition, which was displayed at several locations including in the art gallery of the [[University of California, Irvine]] and, later, the San Francisco Museum of Art.<ref name=\"LAT1966\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Contemporary Ceramics Exhibit| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =October 30, 1966 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/382266548/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LATWallop\">{{cite news | last=Wilson| first=William| title =Ceramics with a Wallop| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =November 4, 1966 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/382323786/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SFE1967\">{{cite news | last=Fried| first=Alexander| title =New Pottery May Leak, but It's Different| newspaper =The San Francisco Examiner| publisher =| date =January 20, 1967 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/458724430/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 1970, his work was featured alongside [[Robert Arneson]], [[Ron Nagle]], and [[David Gilhooly]]'s in an exhibit at the [[Moore College of Art and Design|Moore College of Art]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"PI1970\">{{cite news | last=Donohoe| first=Victoria| title =Quality, Vitality in Ceramic Sculpture| newspaper =The Philadelphia Inquirer| publisher =| date = January 18, 1970| url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/167909830/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 1971, Frimkess was diagnosed with [[multiple sclerosis]]. His subsequent focus on rehab and physical therapy took time away from his ceramic work and limited his output. He continues to throw the pots, and his wife Magdalena Suarez Frimkess would glaze and decorate them.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"NYTBlog\">{{cite news | last=Hadis| first=Diego| title =An 84-Year-Old Ceramist\u2019s New York Moment| newspaper =The New York Times| publisher =| date =March 3, 2014 | url =https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/03/03/on-view-an-84-year-old-ceramists-new-york-moment/| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Ecology Krater II (Out Biking with Aunt Samantha) (2057189580).jpg|thumb|''Out Biking with Aunt Samantha'' by Michael Frimkess, as displayed in the Renwick Gallery]]\nIn 1976, Frimkess' work was featured at the ''Clay: The Medium and the Method'' exhibition held at the art gallery of the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]]. A year later, his work was displayed at the [[Los Angeles Institute of Contemporary Art]] for their exhibition entitled ''Foundations in Clay''.<ref name=\"Studio\">{{cite book |last=Drexler Lynn |first=Martha |date=December 1, 2015 |title=American Studio Ceramics: Innovation and Identity, 1940 to 1979 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pUTOCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA318&dq=%22University+of+California,+Santa+Barbara%22+%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHosKO8rbdAhXL5lQKHbUGB1kQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22University%20of%20California%2C%20Santa%20Barbara%22%20%22michael%20frimkess%22&f=false |location= |publisher=Yale University Press |page=318 |isbn=978-0300212730 |author-link= }}</ref> The latter exhibition was considered an update of the ''Abstract Expressionist Ceramics'' exhibition from 1966 with five of the six artists returning, including Peter Voulkos, Ron Nagle, Kenneth Price, and John Mason.<ref name=\"LAT1977\">{{cite news | last=Wilson| first=William| title =Ceramics \u2014 Craft and Confusion| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =May 10, 1977 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/383568682/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> That year, the James Willis Gallery in [[San Francisco]] also displayed a 17-year retrospective of Frimkess' work.<ref name=\"SFE1977\">{{cite news | last=Friedman| first=Mickey| title =A browser's weekend ramble through galleries| newspaper =The San Francisco Examiner| publisher =| date =April 21, 1977 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/462673484/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> Another retrospective of his solo and collaborative work was held in 1982 at the [[Garth Clark]] Gallery in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"LAT1982\">{{cite news | last=Pincus| first=Robert L.| title =Galleries - Wilshire Center| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =April 23, 1982 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/389031678/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy 1988, Frimkess' work could be found in the [[Smithsonian Institution]], [[American Craft Museum]], and the [[National Museum of Modern Art, Kyoto|National Museum of Modern Art]] in [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]]. That year, his work was also featured as part of an exhibition at the [[Fashion Institute of Technology]] called ''Extended Visions'' which displayed work from artists with multiple sclerosis.<ref name=\"NYDN1988\">{{cite news | last=Shepard| first=Joan| title =Show to focus on vision of artists with MS| newspaper =New York Daily News| publisher =| date =July 10, 1988 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/465498326/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2000, Frimkess and his wife held an exhibition of their work at [[Louis Stern Fine Arts]] entitled, ''Vessels of Satire: The Art of Magdalena and Michael Frimkess''. In 2001, the two provided an official oral history of their lives and work to the Smithsonian Institution's [[Archives of American Art]].<ref name=\"AAA\"/><ref name=\"LAT2000\"/> In 2003, they displayed some of their work at [[Little Tokyo, Los Angeles|Little Tokyo]] Clayworks in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"LAT2003\">{{cite news | last=Keeps| first=David A.| title =Pottery, with personality thrown in| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =October 16, 2003 | url =http://www.latimes.com/la-hm-homeworks16oct16204418-story.html#| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> Beginning in 2012, their work started being displayed at South Willard, a menswear shop also in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"NYT2014\">{{cite news | last=Finkel| first=Jori| title =Biennial\u2019s Bright Young Things, Ages 77 and 84| newspaper =The New York Times| publisher =| date =July 15, 2014 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/arts/design/frimkess-ceramics-have-their-moment-at-hammer-museum.html| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Willard\">{{cite web |url=http://www.southwillard.com/collections/shop-exhibit/magdalena-suarez-frimkess-and-michael-frimkess/ |title=Magdalena Suarez Frimkess and Michael Frimkess|publisher=South Willard |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn 2013, some of Frimkess' early work was displayed at an exhibition called ''Grapevine'' at the David Kordansky Gallery in [[Culver City, California]].<ref name=\"KCRW\">{{cite news | last=Drohojowska-Philp| first=Hunter| title =Grapevine: Magdalena Suarez Frimkess, Michael Frimkess, John Mason, Ron Nagle, Peter Shire| newspaper =| publisher =KCRW| date =August 1, 2013 | url =https://www.kcrw.com/news-culture/shows/art-talk/grapevine-magdalena-suarez-frimkess-michael-frimkess-john-mason-ron-nagle-peter-shire| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In March 2014, the Frimkesses' collaborative work was on display at [[White Columns]] in New York.<ref name=\"NYTBlog\"/> Their work was again featured at the [[Hammer Museum]]'s biennial exhibition, ''Made in L.A.'' in August 2014. The couple was also honored with the ''Made in L.A.'' Mohn Career Achievement Award.<ref name=\"NYT2014\"/><ref name=\"LAT2014\">{{cite news | last=Gelt| first=Jessica| title =Hammer Museum announces winners of 2014 Made in L.A. Mohn Awards| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =August 19, 2014 | url =http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-made-in-la-awards-winners-20140818-story.html| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2016, their work was featured at an exhibition called ''Routine Pleasures'' at the MAK Center in [[West Hollywood]], California.<ref name=\"LAT2016\">{{cite news | last=Miranda| first=Carolina A.| title =Datebook: An all-American collection, art in a train station, genre-bending painting| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =August 4, 2016 | url =http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/miranda/la-et-cam-phillips-collection-ocma-20160804-snap-story.html| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn addition to exhibitions, Frimkess' work has appeared in numerous publications, including Ceramics Monthly, American Ceramics, and Craft Horizons magazines. In 1966 Frimkess wrote an article for Craft Horizons entitled, \"The Importance of Being Classical,\" and he was later featured in its December 1973 issue (\"Michael Frimkess and the Cultured Pot\").<ref name=\"AAA\"/> More recently, Michael and Magdalena have been profiled in both the Los Angeles Times and the New York Times.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/>\n \n==Artistic style==\n\nFrimkess' early work included a variety of both ceramics and bronze or aluminum sculptures. These early pieces were often more free-form and less utilitarian, taking a cue from his mentor and teacher, Peter Voulkos.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"AmerPotters\"/><ref name=\"SFE1963\"/> His interest and skill in making classical pottery forms began to increase in the mid-1960s. Examples of his work include Greek volute kraters, Zuni pots, and Chinese ginger jars. He also learned the technique of dry throwing hard clay with no water to make his vessels, resulting in walls that are remarkably light and thin.<ref name=\"AmerPotters\"/><ref name=\"CerArtPerc\"/><ref name=\"NYT2014\"/> In addition, through his expertise and efforts in kiln design and construction, he developed a method of firing stoneware in as little as 55 minutes.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/>\n \nPrior to his multiple sclerosis diagnosis, Frimkess would glaze and paint all of his ceramics, decorating them with contemporary scenes and [[pop art]].<ref name=\"HistAmerCer\"/><ref name=\"LAT1982\"/> The images were often \"vernacular or historical\" and employed the use of cartoon sequences or word balloons<ref name=\"AmerCer\">{{cite book |last=Clark |first=Garth |date=April 1, 1990 |title=American Ceramics: 1876 To the Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=khxVAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyn-X82bbdAhWnsVQKHc0QCWAQ6AEIVDAJ |location= |publisher=Abbeville Press |pages=20\u201324 |isbn=978-0896597433 |author-link= }}</ref> that often satirized problems related to corruption, segregation, and hypocrisy. His work frequently dealt with racial strife,<ref name=\"Tradition\">{{cite book |last=Hall |first=Julie |date=1977 |title=Tradition and change: The New American Craftsman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UhnaAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyn-X82bbdAhWnsVQKHc0QCWAQ6AEITzAI |location= |publisher=Dutton |pages=182\u2013184 |isbn=978-0525221951 |author-link= }}</ref> and he often drew on his childhood growing up in a predominately [[Chicano]], [[Japanese people|Japanese]], and [[African-American|Black]] neighborhood. His pots were meant to symbolize an ideal \"melting pot.\"<ref name=\"AmerPotters\"/><ref name=\"LAT1982\"/>\n\nSince his multiple sclerosis diagnosis in 1971, most of the art painted on his pots has been done by his wife, Magdalena Suarez Frimkess.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/> While her art has similar themes, it evokes a different cultural experience.<ref name=\"AmerCer\"/> Her glazes and paintings feature pop art icons like [[Minnie Mouse]] and [[Condorito]], but they also employ [[folk art]] combined with a variety of historical references. In general, neither of the two has any input on the other's work.<ref name=\"NYT2014\"/><ref name=\"NYT2017\">{{cite news | last=Smith| first=Roberta| title =What to See in New York Art Galleries This Week| newspaper =The New York Times| publisher =| date =October 4, 2017 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/04/arts/design/what-to-see-in-new-york-art-galleries-this-week.html| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> Both continue to work and reside in Venice, California.<ref name=\"NYTBlog\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frimkess, Michael}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American ceramists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Otis College of Art and Design alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American ceramic artist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Michael Frimkess\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       =\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1937|01|08}}\n| birth_place   = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| residence     = [[Venice, California]]\n| education     = [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in [[Ceramics]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Otis College of Art and Design]]\n| nationality   =\n| other_names   =\n| occupation    = [[Ceramist]]\n| years_active  = 1955\u2013present\n| spouse        = Magdalena Suarez Frimkess\n| known_for     =\n| movement      = [[California Clay Movement]]\n| notable_works =\n}}\n\n'''Michael Frimkess''' (born January 8, 1937) is an American [[ceramic art]]ist who lives in [[Venice, California]]. In the 1950s and 60s, he was a pupil of [[Peter Voulkos]], a prominent figure in the [[California Clay Movement]]. Frimkess' [[pottery]] is noted for its classical style, employing forms from [[Pottery of ancient Greece|Greek]], [[Chinese ceramics|Chinese]], and [[Ceramics of indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous American]] antiquity. His wife and collaborator, Magdalena Suarez Frimkess, paints his ceramic pieces often using anachronistic, contemporary images like [[Minnie Mouse]] or [[Condorito]]. He is also well-known for his innovative wheel-throwing and firing techniques.\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrimkess was born on January 8, 1937<ref name=\"AAA\">{{cite news | last=Karlstrom| first=Paul| title =Oral history interview with Michael and Magdalena Suarez Frimkess, 2001 March 8-April 17| newspaper =| publisher =Archives of American Art| date =March 8, 2001 | url =https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-michael-and-magdalena-suarez-frimkess-13128#transcript| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> in [[Eastside Los Angeles|East]] [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]. He grew up largely in the neighborhood of [[Boyle Heights, Los Angeles|Boyle Heights]]<ref name=\"LAT2000\">{{cite news | last=Muchnic| first=Suzanne| title =Their Lives Poured Into Clay| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =November 19, 2000 | url =http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/19/entertainment/ca-54053| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> and claimed to have been among one of the last Jewish families in the area.<ref name=\"AmerPotters\">{{cite book |last=Clark |first=Garth |date=January 1, 1981 |title=American Potters: The Work of 20 Modern Masters |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q2NQAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjutMvp27bdAhUCqVQKHQ39Ax44ChDoAQgxMAI |location= |publisher=Watson-Guptill |page=41 |isbn=978-0823002139 |author-link=Garth Clark }}</ref> His father, Lou Frimkess, was an artist and graphic designer.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"LATLou\">{{cite news | last=Fitzgerald| first=Patrick| title =Landmark Designer| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =November 26, 2000 | url =http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/26/entertainment/ca-57261| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> He was exposed to fine art early in his childhood, receiving drawing and sculpting lessons, and being taken to numerous museum exhibitions. Frimkess learned how to play the [[saxophone]] and [[piano]] in his youth and aspired to become a jazz musician.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"Hammer2014\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Magdalena Suarez Frimkess & Michael Frimkess| newspaper =| publisher =Hammer Museum| date =2014 | url =https://hammer.ucla.edu/made-in-la-2014/magdalena-suarez-frimkess-michael-frimkess/| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> At age 15, his family moved to [[Hollywood]] and he would graduate from [[Hollywood High School]] two years later in 1955. In high school, he took up sculpture, which led him to seek out art schools after graduation. At the age of 17 he became the youngest person to receive a scholarship from the [[Otis College of Art and Design]] (then known as the Los Angeles County Art Institute).<ref name=\"AAA\"/><ref name=\"LAT2000\"/>\n \nAfter a year at the college, Frimkess switched his focus to ceramics, a move that he attributes to a [[peyote]]-induced vision of himself throwing a perfectly-shaped vessel.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"ClayToday\">{{cite book |last=Drexler Lynn |first=Martha |date=June 1, 1990 |title=Clay Today: Contemporary Ceramists and Their Work |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QVpQAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjutMvp27bdAhUCqVQKHQ39Ax44ChDoAQhEMAY |location= |publisher=Chronicle Books |page=68 |isbn=978-0877017561 |author-link= }}</ref> In the ceramics department, he studied under Peter Voulkos, perhaps the most notable figure in the California Clay Movement.<ref name=\"Intro\">{{cite news | last=Bartolucci| first=Marisa| title =A New Focus on Mid-Century Ceramist Peter Voulkos| newspaper =| publisher =Introspective| date = January 30, 2017| url =https://www.1stdibs.com/introspective-magazine/peter-voulkos/| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> He also worked alongside sculptors and ceramists like [[Billy Al Bengston]], [[John Mason (artist)|John Mason]], [[Kenneth Price]], [[Paul Soldner]], and others.<ref name=\"ClayToday\"/> In 1956, he was one of 10 young artists to open and display work at a gallery on [[Sunset Boulevard]].<ref name=\"LAT1956\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =In The Galleries - Young Artists| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =June 24, 1956 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/380998990/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 1957, Frimkess worked in a small ceramics factory while on a trip with his family in [[Italy]], where he received additional training in throwing a very hard type of clay.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/>\n \n==Career==\n[[File:Michael Frimkess, Magdalena Suarez Frimkess, Blues for Dr. Banks -Miles Davis-, 1972-74 (11501307495).jpg|thumb|''Blues for Dr. Banks'' by Michael and Magdalena Frimkess]]\nIn the early 1960s, Frimkess went to [[Berkeley, California]] where Peter Voulkos was then teaching at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. While there, he studied bronze and aluminum casting with Voulkos.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/> In 1963, his piece \"Hooker No. 1\" (a bronze sculpture of a television) was displayed at the [[San Francisco Art Institute]]'s Annual exhibition at the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]].<ref name=\"SFE1963\">{{cite news | last=Fried| first=Alexander| title =The Annual: Raw, Rough and Not a Lyrical Note| newspaper =The San Francisco Examiner| publisher =| date =March 31, 1963 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/458553664/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> Also that year at the behest of Voulkos, Frimkess took an internship at the Clay Art Center in [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. It was there that he met his future wife and frequent collaborator, Magdalena Suarez, who had come to the Art Center from [[Venezuela]] as part of a fellowship program.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/> While on the east coast, Frimkess was instructed to visit museums in [[New York City|New York]] and [[Boston]] to study Greek and Chinese forms of pottery. He also began learning the technique of \"dry throwing\" clay rather than using water.<ref name=\"ClayToday\"/><ref name=\"HistAmerCer\">{{cite book |last=Levin |first=Elaine |date=October 6, 1988 |title=The History of American Ceramics: From Pipkins and Bean Pots to Contemporary Forms |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=unpQAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijt-et47bdAhUQKHwKHWIJA0U4ChDoAQhJMAc |location= |publisher=Harry N. Abrams |page=232 |isbn=978-0810911727 |author-link= }}</ref> Much of his work after 1965 replicated classical forms like Greek volute [[kraters]], [[Zuni]] pots, and Chinese ginger jars.<ref name=\"AmerPotters\"/><ref name=\"CerArtPerc\">{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CfVUAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjl9tHt5LbdAhWT7Z8KHVUmCgw4FBDoAQg7MAQ |title=Ceramics, Art and Perception, Issues 47-50|publisher=Ceramics, Art and Perception |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn 1966, his work was featured in the ''Abstract Expressionist Ceramics'' exhibition, which was displayed at several locations including in the art gallery of the [[University of California, Irvine]] and, later, the San Francisco Museum of Art.<ref name=\"LAT1966\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Contemporary Ceramics Exhibit| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =October 30, 1966 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/382266548/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LATWallop\">{{cite news | last=Wilson| first=William| title =Ceramics with a Wallop| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =November 4, 1966 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/382323786/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"SFE1967\">{{cite news | last=Fried| first=Alexander| title =New Pottery May Leak, but It's Different| newspaper =The San Francisco Examiner| publisher =| date =January 20, 1967 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/458724430/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 1970, his work was featured alongside [[Robert Arneson]], [[Ron Nagle]], and [[David Gilhooly]]'s in an exhibit at the [[Moore College of Art and Design|Moore College of Art]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"PI1970\">{{cite news | last=Donohoe| first=Victoria| title =Quality, Vitality in Ceramic Sculpture| newspaper =The Philadelphia Inquirer| publisher =| date = January 18, 1970| url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/167909830/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 1971, Frimkess was diagnosed with [[multiple sclerosis]]. His subsequent focus on rehab and physical therapy took time away from his ceramic work and limited his output. He continues to throw the pots, and his wife Magdalena Suarez Frimkess would glaze and decorate them.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"NYTBlog\">{{cite news | last=Hadis| first=Diego| title =An 84-Year-Old Ceramist\u2019s New York Moment| newspaper =The New York Times| publisher =| date =March 3, 2014 | url =https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/03/03/on-view-an-84-year-old-ceramists-new-york-moment/| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Ecology Krater II (Out Biking with Aunt Samantha) (2057189580).jpg|thumb|''Out Biking with Aunt Samantha'' by Michael Frimkess, as displayed in the Renwick Gallery]]\nIn 1976, Frimkess' work was featured at the ''Clay: The Medium and the Method'' exhibition held at the art gallery of the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]]. A year later, his work was displayed at the [[Los Angeles Institute of Contemporary Art]] for their exhibition entitled ''Foundations in Clay''.<ref name=\"Studio\">{{cite book |last=Drexler Lynn |first=Martha |date=December 1, 2015 |title=American Studio Ceramics: Innovation and Identity, 1940 to 1979 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pUTOCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA318&dq=%22University+of+California,+Santa+Barbara%22+%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHosKO8rbdAhXL5lQKHbUGB1kQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22University%20of%20California%2C%20Santa%20Barbara%22%20%22michael%20frimkess%22&f=false |location= |publisher=Yale University Press |page=318 |isbn=978-0300212730 |author-link= }}</ref> The latter exhibition was considered an update of the ''Abstract Expressionist Ceramics'' exhibition from 1966 with five of the six artists returning, including Peter Voulkos, Ron Nagle, Kenneth Price, and John Mason.<ref name=\"LAT1977\">{{cite news | last=Wilson| first=William| title =Ceramics \u2014 Craft and Confusion| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =May 10, 1977 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/383568682/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> That year, the James Willis Gallery in [[San Francisco]] also displayed a 17-year retrospective of Frimkess' work.<ref name=\"SFE1977\">{{cite news | last=Friedman| first=Mickey| title =A browser's weekend ramble through galleries| newspaper =The San Francisco Examiner| publisher =| date =April 21, 1977 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/462673484/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> Another retrospective of his solo and collaborative work was held in 1982 at the [[Garth Clark]] Gallery in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"LAT1982\">{{cite news | last=Pincus| first=Robert L.| title =Galleries - Wilshire Center| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =April 23, 1982 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/389031678/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy 1988, Frimkess' work could be found in the [[Smithsonian Institution]], [[American Craft Museum]], and the [[National Museum of Modern Art, Kyoto|National Museum of Modern Art]] in [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]]. That year, his work was also featured as part of an exhibition at the [[Fashion Institute of Technology]] called ''Extended Visions'' which displayed work from artists with multiple sclerosis.<ref name=\"NYDN1988\">{{cite news | last=Shepard| first=Joan| title =Show to focus on vision of artists with MS| newspaper =New York Daily News| publisher =| date =July 10, 1988 | url =https://www.newspapers.com/image/465498326/?terms=%22michael%2Bfrimkess%22| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2000, Frimkess and his wife held an exhibition of their work at [[Louis Stern Fine Arts]] entitled, ''Vessels of Satire: The Art of Magdalena and Michael Frimkess''. In 2001, the two provided an official oral history of their lives and work to the Smithsonian Institution's [[Archives of American Art]].<ref name=\"AAA\"/><ref name=\"LAT2000\"/> In 2003, they displayed some of their work at [[Little Tokyo, Los Angeles|Little Tokyo]] Clayworks in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"LAT2003\">{{cite news | last=Keeps| first=David A.| title =Pottery, with personality thrown in| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =October 16, 2003 | url =http://www.latimes.com/la-hm-homeworks16oct16204418-story.html#| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> Beginning in 2012, their work started being displayed at South Willard, a menswear shop also in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"NYT2014\">{{cite news | last=Finkel| first=Jori| title =Biennial\u2019s Bright Young Things, Ages 77 and 84| newspaper =The New York Times| publisher =| date =July 15, 2014 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/arts/design/frimkess-ceramics-have-their-moment-at-hammer-museum.html| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Willard\">{{cite web |url=http://www.southwillard.com/collections/shop-exhibit/magdalena-suarez-frimkess-and-michael-frimkess/ |title=Magdalena Suarez Frimkess and Michael Frimkess|publisher=South Willard |accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn 2013, some of Frimkess' early work was displayed at an exhibition called ''Grapevine'' at the David Kordansky Gallery in [[Culver City, California]].<ref name=\"KCRW\">{{cite news | last=Drohojowska-Philp| first=Hunter| title =Grapevine: Magdalena Suarez Frimkess, Michael Frimkess, John Mason, Ron Nagle, Peter Shire| newspaper =| publisher =KCRW| date =August 1, 2013 | url =https://www.kcrw.com/news-culture/shows/art-talk/grapevine-magdalena-suarez-frimkess-michael-frimkess-john-mason-ron-nagle-peter-shire| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In March 2014, the Frimkesses' collaborative work was on display at [[White Columns]] in New York.<ref name=\"NYTBlog\"/> Their work was again featured at the [[Hammer Museum]]'s biennial exhibition, ''Made in L.A.'' in August 2014. The couple was also honored with the ''Made in L.A.'' Mohn Career Achievement Award.<ref name=\"NYT2014\"/><ref name=\"LAT2014\">{{cite news | last=Gelt| first=Jessica| title =Hammer Museum announces winners of 2014 Made in L.A. Mohn Awards| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =August 19, 2014 | url =http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-hammer-museum-made-in-la-awards-winners-20140818-story.html| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2016, their work was featured at an exhibition called ''Routine Pleasures'' at the MAK Center in [[West Hollywood]], California.<ref name=\"LAT2016\">{{cite news | last=Miranda| first=Carolina A.| title =Datebook: An all-American collection, art in a train station, genre-bending painting| newspaper =Los Angeles Times| publisher =| date =August 4, 2016 | url =http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/miranda/la-et-cam-phillips-collection-ocma-20160804-snap-story.html| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn addition to exhibitions, Frimkess' work has appeared in numerous publications, including Ceramics Monthly, American Ceramics, and Craft Horizons magazines. In 1966 Frimkess wrote an article for Craft Horizons entitled, \"The Importance of Being Classical,\" and he was later featured in its December 1973 issue (\"Michael Frimkess and the Cultured Pot\").<ref name=\"AAA\"/> More recently, Michael and Magdalena have been profiled in both the Los Angeles Times and the New York Times.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/>\n \n==Artistic style==\n\nFrimkess' early work included a variety of both ceramics and bronze or aluminum sculptures. These early pieces were often more free-form and less utilitarian, taking a cue from his mentor and teacher, Peter Voulkos.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/><ref name=\"AmerPotters\"/><ref name=\"SFE1963\"/> His interest and skill in making classical pottery forms began to increase in the mid-1960s. Examples of his work include Greek volute kraters, Zuni pots, and Chinese ginger jars. He also learned the technique of dry throwing hard clay with no water to make his vessels, resulting in walls that are remarkably light and thin.<ref name=\"AmerPotters\"/><ref name=\"CerArtPerc\"/><ref name=\"NYT2014\"/> In addition, through his expertise and efforts in kiln design and construction, he developed a method of firing stoneware in as little as 55 minutes.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/>\n \nPrior to his multiple sclerosis diagnosis, Frimkess would glaze and paint all of his ceramics, decorating them with contemporary scenes and [[pop art]].<ref name=\"HistAmerCer\"/><ref name=\"LAT1982\"/> The images were often \"vernacular or historical\" and employed the use of cartoon sequences or word balloons<ref name=\"AmerCer\">{{cite book |last=Clark |first=Garth |date=April 1, 1990 |title=American Ceramics: 1876 To the Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=khxVAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyn-X82bbdAhWnsVQKHc0QCWAQ6AEIVDAJ |location= |publisher=Abbeville Press |pages=20\u201324 |isbn=978-0896597433 |author-link= }}</ref> that often satirized problems related to corruption, segregation, and hypocrisy. His work frequently dealt with racial strife,<ref name=\"Tradition\">{{cite book |last=Hall |first=Julie |date=1977 |title=Tradition and change: The New American Craftsman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UhnaAAAAMAAJ&q=%22michael+frimkess%22&dq=%22michael+frimkess%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyn-X82bbdAhWnsVQKHc0QCWAQ6AEITzAI |location= |publisher=Dutton |pages=182\u2013184 |isbn=978-0525221951 |author-link= }}</ref> and he often drew on his childhood growing up in a predominately [[Chicano]], [[Japanese people|Japanese]], and [[African-American|Black]] neighborhood. His pots were meant to symbolize an ideal \"melting pot.\"<ref name=\"AmerPotters\"/><ref name=\"LAT1982\"/>\n\nSince his multiple sclerosis diagnosis in 1971, most of the art painted on his pots has been done by his wife, Magdalena Suarez Frimkess.<ref name=\"LAT2000\"/> While her art has similar themes, it evokes a different cultural experience.<ref name=\"AmerCer\"/> Her glazes and paintings feature pop art icons like [[Minnie Mouse]] and [[Condorito]], but they also employ [[folk art]] combined with a variety of historical references. In general, neither of the two has any input on the other's work.<ref name=\"NYT2014\"/><ref name=\"NYT2017\">{{cite news | last=Smith| first=Roberta| title =What to See in New York Art Galleries This Week| newspaper =The New York Times| publisher =| date =October 4, 2017 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/04/arts/design/what-to-see-in-new-york-art-galleries-this-week.html| accessdate =November 13, 2018}}</ref> Both continue to work and reside in Venice, California.<ref name=\"NYTBlog\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frimkess, Michael}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American ceramists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Otis College of Art and Design alumni]]\n", "name_user": "DarkerBlue599", "label": "safe", "comment": "Interlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Frimkess"}
{"title_page": "Bratislava Lama\u010d railway station", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n| name = Bratislava-Lama\u010d\n| type =\n| image = Bratislava Lamac Railway Station2.JPG\n| image_caption = Bratislava - Lama\u010d railway station\n| address = Lama\u010dsk\u00e1 cesta&nbsp;6530/22<br>84103 Lama\u010d<br />[[File:Coat of Arms of Lama\u010d.svg|x16px]] [[Lama\u010d]]<br />[[Bratislava IV]]<br />{{flag|Bratislava Region}}\n| country = {{flag|Slovakia}}\n| coordinates = {{coord|48|11|09|N|17|02|55|E|region:SK-BL|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| distance = {{convert|49.147|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[K\u00faty]]\n| elevation =\n| line = [[Bratislava]] \u2013 [[K\u00faty]]\n| other =\n* Public transport buses and [[night buses]] stop next to the railway station\n| platform = 3\n| opened =\n| closed =\n| architect =\n| rebuilt =\n| electrified =\n| owned = [[\u017deleznice Slovenskej republiky]] (\u017dSR)\n| operator = [[\u017delezni\u010dn\u00e1 spolo\u010dnos\u0165 Slovensko]] (\u017dSSK)\n| map_type = Slovakia\n| map_size = 300\n| route_map = [[image:Bratislava l.png|250px|none|Localisation within the [[Bratislava]] city rail network]]\n| map_state = expanded\n}}\n\n'''Bratislava Lama\u010d railway station''' ({{lang-sk|\u017delezni\u010dn\u00e1 stanica Bratislava-Lama\u010d}}) is a small [[railway station]] (technically a train halt) inside the [[Lama\u010d]] borough of [[Bratislava]], [[Slovakia]]. Until 1947 the station was called \"Lama\u010d\". The railway station is administered under [[Bratislava hlavn\u00e1 stanica]], with the station master ({{lang-sk|prednosta}}) residing there as well. It lies at the edge of the [[Lama\u010d]] and [[D\u00fabravka, Bratislava|D\u00fabravka]] boroughs of Bratislava.\n\nBratislava Lama\u010d railway station is the smallest true [[railway station]] in Bratislava. It contains four tracks of rails allowing the trains to cross tracks or the express trains to overtake slower passenger or freight trains.<ref>http://www.zeleznicne.info/view.php?nazevclanku=zeleznicna-stanica-bratislava%96lamac&cisloclanku=2010030006</ref> The station building was reconstructed in 2007.\n\n== History ==\nIn the past, stone from the nearby [[quarry]] was being loaded onto trains here. The narrow-rail line for this purpose was built in 1924.\n\nOn 21 May 2012 a 41-year-old woman died when she stumbled at the first platform when crossing the lines, falling down under a passing train. The accident caused seven trains to be delayed for a total time of 201 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u017denu pri prech\u00e1dzan\u00ed cez ko\u013eaje v Lama\u010di usmrtil vlak (A woman died after collision with a train while crossing the rails in Lama\u010d)|url=http://www.bratislavskenoviny.sk/najnovsie-spravy-z-bratislavy/verejny-poriadok/zenu-pri-prechadzani-cez-kolaje-v-lamaci-usmrtil-vlak.html?page_id=283101|accessdate=23 May 2012|newspaper=Bratislavsk\u00e9 Noviny|date=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Rail lines ==\nThe following is a list of rail lines crossing this station.\n* Line No. 110: Bratislava - [[K\u00faty]]\n\n== Access ==\n[[image:Bratislava Lamac Railway Station5.JPG|thumb|left|\u017dST Lama\u010d public bus stop in [[Bratislava]]. The actual bus stops (in both directions) are marked by red buses]]\n\nA few meters away from the main station building there is a public bus stop called ''\u017delezni\u010dn\u00e1 stanica Lama\u010d'', sometimes officially abbreviated to ''\u017dST Lama\u010d''. Buses no. 30, no. 37, no. 38, no. 63 and no. 92 stop here as well as night busses no. N21 and no. N37. The railway station is a short walk away for many people from [[Lama\u010d]] and [[D\u00fabravka, Bratislava|D\u00fabravka]] boroughs of Bratislava.\n\nThis bus stop serves also as a minor intercity bus stop for buses headed towards [[Stupava, Malacky District|Stupava]] and [[Malacky]] in the [[Z\u00e1horie]] region of Slovakia.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.vlaky.net/servis/galeria.asp?id=2056 Page about the railway station with pictures in Slovak]\n* [http://www.rail.sk/arp/slovakia/zst/131664.htm Pictures of the former look of this railway station]\n\n{{Nsb next start}}\n{{Nsb next line\n|line = ''\u017dSR No. 110 [[Bratislava]] - [[K\u00faty]] - [[B\u0159eclav]]''\n|prestation = ''[[Bratislava-\u017delezn\u00e1 studienka Railway Station]]''\n|poststation = ''[[Dev\u00ednska Nov\u00e1 Ves Railway Station]]''\n}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bratislava Lamac railway station}}\n[[Category:Railway stations in Bratislava]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n| name = Bratislava-Lama\u010d\n| type =\n| image = Bratislava Lamac Railway Station2.JPG\n| image_caption = Bratislava - Lama\u010d railway station\n| address = Lama\u010dsk\u00e1 cesta&nbsp;6530/22<br>84103 Lama\u010d<br />[[File:Lamac erb.gif|x15px]] [[Lama\u010d]]<br />[[Bratislava IV]]<br />{{flag|Bratislava Region}}\n| country = {{flag|Slovakia}}\n| coordinates = {{coord|48|11|09|N|17|02|55|E|region:SK-BL|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| distance = {{convert|49.147|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[K\u00faty]]\n| elevation =\n| line = [[Bratislava]] \u2013 [[K\u00faty]]\n| other =\n* Public transport buses and [[night buses]] stop next to the railway station\n| platform = 3\n| opened =\n| closed =\n| architect =\n| rebuilt =\n| electrified =\n| owned = [[\u017deleznice Slovenskej republiky]] (\u017dSR)\n| operator = [[\u017delezni\u010dn\u00e1 spolo\u010dnos\u0165 Slovensko]] (\u017dSSK)\n| map_type = Slovakia\n| map_size = 300\n| route_map = [[image:Bratislava l.png|250px|none|Localisation within the [[Bratislava]] city rail network]]\n| map_state = expanded\n}}\n\n'''Bratislava Lama\u010d railway station''' ({{lang-sk|\u017delezni\u010dn\u00e1 stanica Bratislava-Lama\u010d}}) is a small [[railway station]] (technically a train halt) inside the [[Lama\u010d]] borough of [[Bratislava]], [[Slovakia]]. Until 1947 the station was called \"Lama\u010d\". The railway station is administered under [[Bratislava hlavn\u00e1 stanica]], with the station master ({{lang-sk|prednosta}}) residing there as well. It lies at the edge of the [[Lama\u010d]] and [[D\u00fabravka, Bratislava|D\u00fabravka]] boroughs of Bratislava.\n\nBratislava Lama\u010d railway station is the smallest true [[railway station]] in Bratislava. It contains four tracks of rails allowing the trains to cross tracks or the express trains to overtake slower passenger or freight trains.<ref>http://www.zeleznicne.info/view.php?nazevclanku=zeleznicna-stanica-bratislava%96lamac&cisloclanku=2010030006</ref> The station building was reconstructed in 2007.\n\n== History ==\nIn the past, stone from the nearby [[quarry]] was being loaded onto trains here. The narrow-rail line for this purpose was built in 1924.\n\nOn 21 May 2012 a 41-year-old woman died when she stumbled at the first platform when crossing the lines, falling down under a passing train. The accident caused seven trains to be delayed for a total time of 201 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u017denu pri prech\u00e1dzan\u00ed cez ko\u013eaje v Lama\u010di usmrtil vlak (A woman died after collision with a train while crossing the rails in Lama\u010d)|url=http://www.bratislavskenoviny.sk/najnovsie-spravy-z-bratislavy/verejny-poriadok/zenu-pri-prechadzani-cez-kolaje-v-lamaci-usmrtil-vlak.html?page_id=283101|accessdate=23 May 2012|newspaper=Bratislavsk\u00e9 Noviny|date=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Rail lines ==\nThe following is a list of rail lines crossing this station.\n* Line No. 110: Bratislava - [[K\u00faty]]\n\n== Access ==\n[[image:Bratislava Lamac Railway Station5.JPG|thumb|left|\u017dST Lama\u010d public bus stop in [[Bratislava]]. The actual bus stops (in both directions) are marked by red buses]]\n\nA few meters away from the main station building there is a public bus stop called ''\u017delezni\u010dn\u00e1 stanica Lama\u010d'', sometimes officially abbreviated to ''\u017dST Lama\u010d''. Buses no. 30, no. 37, no. 38, no. 63 and no. 92 stop here as well as night busses no. N21 and no. N37. The railway station is a short walk away for many people from [[Lama\u010d]] and [[D\u00fabravka, Bratislava|D\u00fabravka]] boroughs of Bratislava.\n\nThis bus stop serves also as a minor intercity bus stop for buses headed towards [[Stupava, Malacky District|Stupava]] and [[Malacky]] in the [[Z\u00e1horie]] region of Slovakia.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.vlaky.net/servis/galeria.asp?id=2056 Page about the railway station with pictures in Slovak]\n* [http://www.rail.sk/arp/slovakia/zst/131664.htm Pictures of the former look of this railway station]\n\n{{Nsb next start}}\n{{Nsb next line\n|line = ''\u017dSR No. 110 [[Bratislava]] - [[K\u00faty]] - [[B\u0159eclav]]''\n|prestation = ''[[Bratislava-\u017delezn\u00e1 studienka Railway Station]]''\n|poststation = ''[[Dev\u00ednska Nov\u00e1 Ves Railway Station]]''\n}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bratislava Lamac railway station}}\n[[Category:Railway stations in Bratislava]]\n", "name_user": "Krumpi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bratislava_Lama%C4%8D_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Serve the Servants", "text_new": "{{short description|1993 song by Nirvana}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name           = Serve the Servants\n| cover          = Nirvana - Serve the Servants cover art.jpg\n| caption        = Single cover art by Kurt Cobain<ref>Nirvana (2013). ''In Utero - Super Deluxe'' - linear notes</ref>\n| artist         = [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n| album          = [[In Utero (album)|In Utero]]\n| released       = {{Start date|1993|09|13}}\n| recorded       = February 13\u201326, 1993\n| studio        = [[Pachyderm Studio|Pachyderm]], [[Cannon Falls, Minnesota]]\n| genre         = [[Grunge]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2014/08/the-50-best-grunge-songs.html |title=The 50 Best Grunge Songs |last=Danaher |first=Michael |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date=August 4, 2014}}</ref>\n| length         = {{Duration|m=3|s=36}}\n| label          = [[DGC Records|DGC]]\n| writer         = [[Kurt Cobain]]\n| producer       = [[Steve Albini]]\n| tracks         = {{In Utero tracks}}\n}}\n'''\"Serve the Servants\"''' is a song by the American [[rock music|rock]] band [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], written by vocalist and guitarist, [[Kurt Cobain]]. It is the first track on their third and final studio album ''[[In Utero (album)|In Utero]]'', released in September 1993.\n\n==Origin and recording==\n\nWritten in 1992, \"Serve the Servants\" was the only ''In Utero'' song that had never been recorded as a demo by the full band prior to being recorded for the album. As Nirvana's bassist [[Krist Novoselic]] remembers, it was brought to the studio \"pretty much done\" by Cobain.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G.|title=In Utero|date=2006|publisher=Continium|location=United States|isbn=0-8264-1776-0|page=58}}</ref> The album was recorded in February 1993 by [[Steve Albini]] at [[Pachyderm Studio]] in [[Cannon Falls, Minnesota]].\n\nThe song was performed, along with \"[[Dumb (Nirvana song)|Dumb]],\" at Nirvana's final television appearance, on February 23, 1994 in [[Rome, Italy]] for the ''[[RAI]]'' television show, ''Tunnel''.\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n\nJournalist Gillian G. Gaar described \"Serve the Servants\" as \"a straight-ahead rock song, arguably the most straightforward song on ''In Utero'',\" and noted that its steady volume was a departure from the frequently-used \"soft/loud Nirvana dynamic.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G.|title=In Utero|date=2006|publisher=Continium|location=United States|isbn=0-8264-1776-0|page=58}}</ref> Author Chuck Crisafulli wrote that the song was among the most \"[[rock and roll|rock n' roll]]\" tracks the band ever recorded and provided an energizing and satisfying opener to the album, which immediately dispelled rumors that ''In Utero'' would be excessively abrasive and unlistenable.<ref name=\"Crisafulli\">{{cite book |last1=Crisafulli |first1=Chuck |title=Teen Spirit: The Stories Behind Every Nirvana Song |date=1996 |publisher=Omnibus Press |location=London |isbn=0711958092 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/teenspiritstorie0000cris/page/82 82-83] |url=https://archive.org/details/teenspiritstorie0000cris/page/82 }}</ref>\n\nThe song's autobiographical lyrics address both Cobain's struggles with fame and his family life.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G.|title=In Utero|date=2006|publisher=Continium|location=United States|isbn=0-8264-1776-0|page=58}}</ref> The opening lyrics, ''\"Teenage angst has paid off well, now I'm bored and old,\"'' were a commentary on Cobain's public image, and his life as a celebrity since the unexpected success of Nirvana's second album, ''[[Nevermind]]'', released in September 1991.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G.|title=In Utero|date=2006|publisher=Continium|location=United States|isbn=0-8264-1776-0|page=58}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Crawford |first=Anwen |date=2014 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jz5iBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT79&dq=Nirvana+Serve+the+Servants&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUhMGOkqTeAhWMYlAKHelzB804KBDoAQhTMAg#v=onepage&q=Nirvana%20Serve%20the%20Servants&f=false |title=Hole's Live Through This |page=(no page numbers) | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA |accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> The lyric, ''\"If she floats then she is not a witch like we had thought\"'', was an attack on the media for its perceived misrepresentation of Cobain's wife [[Courtney Love]], vocalist and guitarist of the American rock band [[Hole (band)|Hole]], comparing her treatment to a [[witchhunt]] and the practice of subjecting women accused of [[witchcraft]] to a public [[dunking|ordeal by water]].<ref name=\"Crisafulli\"/>\n\nIn his 1993 biography ''[[Come as You Are: The Story of Nirvana]]'', [[Michael Azerrad]] stated that Cobain sent a personal and direct message to his father with the lines, ''\"I tried hard to have a father/but instead I had a dad/I just want you to know that I don't hate you anymore/There is nothing I could say that I haven't thought before\"''.<ref name=\"Azerrad\">{{cite book |last=Azerrad |first=Michael |date=1993 |title=Come as You Are: The Story of Nirvana |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qrSDPW6G5ZIC&pg=PA326&dq=Nirvana+Serve+the+Servants&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiar5TFkaTeAhXPmLQKHZyCDtQ4HhDoAQhcMAk#v=onepage&q=Nirvana%20Serve%20the%20Servants&f=false |page=326 |publisher=Crown/Archetype|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> However, Cobain stated that the lines were included at the last minute and that \"they just happen to fit really well\".<ref name=\"Azerrad\"/> Author [[Charles R. Cross]], in his 2001 Cobain biography, ''[[Heavier Than Heaven]]'', also described these lines as bitter lyrics aimed at Cobain's father.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cross |first=Charles. R |date=2012 |title=Heavier Than Heaven |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NWOLAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nirvana+Serve+the+Servants&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSstn-j6TeAhUQY1AKHeksAPAQ6AEIUzAJ#v=onepage&q=Serve%20the%20Servants&f=false |page=(no page numbers) |publisher=[[Hachette UK]]|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> The last line of the chorus ''\"that legendary divorce is such a bore\"'' refers to Cobain being tired of his childhood being plumbed for deep meaning.<ref name=\"Crisafulli\"/>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n\nAccording to the April 2000 edition of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', at one point during Cobain's memorial vigil in April 1994, the song was being \"blasted\" from the loudspeakers while \"an estimated 5,000 kids poured over the fountain, plugging up the spigots, lifting their middle fingers to the skies and howling with gleeful rage.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Weisbard |first=Eric |title=Spin magazine - Nirvana |date=April 2000 |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UMvcbE3u_GkC&pg=PA71&dq=Nirvana+Serve+the+Servants&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSstn-j6TeAhUQY1AKHeksAPAQ6AEIRjAG#v=onepage&q=Nirvana%20Serve%20the%20Servants&f=false |volume=16, No. 4 | publisher=SPIN Media LLC |accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked \"Serve the Servants\" at number 14 in their list of the top 102 Nirvana songs.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=No Apologies: All 102 Nirvana Songs Ranked |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/no-apologies-all-102-nirvana-songs-ranked-175683/serve-the-servants-33723/ |date=2015 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Love named \"Serve the Servants\" as one of her favorite Nirvana songs, also mentioning the ''In Utero'' songs \"[[Heart-Shaped Box]]\" and \"Frances Farmer Will Have Her Revenge on Seattle\", and the ''Nevermind'' song \"[[In Bloom]].\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Moore |first=Sam |date=May 8, 2017 |title=Courtney Love reveals her favourite Nirvana songs |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/courtney-love-reveals-favourite-nirvana-songs-2068017 |website=nme.com |publisher=[[NME]] |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe song's title is referenced by Nirvana's manager Danny Goldberg in the title of his book ''Serving The Servant: Remembering Kurt Cobain'', to be released in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cowdery |first=Katherine |date=August 14, 2018 |title=Former manager pens Kurt Cobain biography for Trapeze |url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/trapeze-publish-biography-kurt-cobain-former-manager-845756 |accessdate=January 1, 2019 |website=thebookseller.com |publisher=[[The Bookseller]]}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and release history==\n===Demo and studio versions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date recorded\n!Studio\n!Producer/recorder\n!Releases\n!Personnel \n|-\n|Winter 1992\n|Cobain residence, Seattle, Washington\n|Kurt Cobain\n|''[[With the Lights Out]]'' (2004)\n|\n*[[Kurt Cobain]]: vocals, guitar<br> \n|-\n|February 12\u201326, 1993\n|[[Pachyderm Studio]], [[Cannon Falls, Minnesota|Cannon Falls]], [[Minnesota]], US\n|[[Steve Albini]]\n|''[[In Utero (album)|In Utero]]'' (1993)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain: vocals, guitar<br> \n*[[Krist Novoselic]]: bass guitar<br>\n*[[Dave Grohl]]: drums\n|}\n\n===Live versions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date recorded\n!Venue\n!Releases\n!Personnel \n|-\n|December 13, 1993\n|[[Central Waterfront, Seattle#Piers 46\u201348|Pier 48]], Seattle, Washington\n|''[[Live and Loud (Nirvana video album)|Live and Loud]]'' (2013)<br>''In Utero (super deluxe)'' (2013)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain: vocals, guitar<br> \n*Krist Novoselic: bass guitar<br>\n*Dave Grohl: drums\n*[[Pat Smear]]: guitar\n|-\n|February 23, 1994\n|''Tunnel'', [[RAI]], [[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n|''Live and Loud'' (2013)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain: vocals, guitar<br> \n*Krist Novoselic: bass guitar<br>\n*Dave Grohl: drums\n*Pat Smear: guitar\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nirvana}}\n[[Category:1993 songs]]\n[[Category:Nirvana (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kurt Cobain]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Steve Albini]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1993 song by Nirvana}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name           = Serve the Servants\n| cover          = Nirvana - Serve the Servants cover art.jpg\n| caption        = Single cover art by Kurt Cobain<ref>Nirvana (2013). ''In Utero - Super Deluxe'' - linear notes</ref>\n| artist         = [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n| album          = [[In Utero (album)|In Utero]]\n| released       = {{Start date|1993|09|13}}\n| recorded       = February 13\u201326, 1993\n| studio        = [[Pachyderm Studio|Pachyderm]], [[Cannon Falls, Minnesota]]\n| genre         = [[Grunge]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2014/08/the-50-best-grunge-songs.html |title=The 50 Best Grunge Songs |last=Danaher |first=Michael |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date=August 4, 2014}}</ref>\n| length         = {{Duration|m=3|s=36}}\n| label          = [[DGC Records|DGC]]\n| writer         = [[Kurt Cobain]]\n| producer       = [[Steve Albini]]\n| tracks         = {{In Utero tracks}}\n}}\n'''\"Serve the Servants\"''' is a song by the American [[rock music|rock]] band [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], written by vocalist and guitarist, [[Kurt Cobain]]. It is the first track on their third and final studio album ''[[In Utero (album)|In Utero]]'', released in September 1993.\n\n==Origin and recording==\n\nWritten in 1992, \"Serve the Servants\" was the only ''In Utero'' song that had never been recorded as a demo by the full band prior to being recorded for the album. As Nirvana's bassist [[Krist Novoselic]] remembers, it was brought to the studio \"pretty much done\" by Cobain.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G.|title=In Utero|date=2006|publisher=Continium|location=United States|isbn=0-8264-1776-0|page=58}}</ref> The album was recorded in February 1993 by [[Steve Albini]] at [[Pachyderm Studio]] in [[Cannon Falls, Minnesota]].\n\nThe song was performed, along with \"[[Dumb (Nirvana song)|Dumb]],\" at Nirvana's final television appearance, on February 23, 1994 in [[Rome, Italy]] for the ''[[RAI]]'' television show, ''Tunnel''.\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n\nJournalist Gillian G. Gaar described \"Serve the Servants\" as \"a straight-ahead rock song, arguably the most straightforward song on ''In Utero'',\" and noted that its steady volume was a departure from the frequently-used \"soft/loud Nirvana dynamic.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G.|title=In Utero|date=2006|publisher=Continium|location=United States|isbn=0-8264-1776-0|page=58}}</ref> Author Chuck Crisafulli wrote that the song was among the most \"[[rock and roll|rock n' roll]]\" tracks the band ever recorded and provided an energizing and satisfying opener to the album, which immediately dispelled rumors that ''In Utero'' would be excessively abrasive and unlistenable.<ref name=\"Crisafulli\">{{cite book |last1=Crisafulli |first1=Chuck |title=Teen Spirit: The Stories Behind Every Nirvana Song |date=1996 |publisher=Omnibus Press |location=London |isbn=0711958092 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/teenspiritstorie0000cris/page/82 82-83] |url=https://archive.org/details/teenspiritstorie0000cris/page/82 }}</ref>\n\nThe song's autobiographical lyrics address both Cobain's struggles with fame and his family life.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G.|title=In Utero|date=2006|publisher=Continium|location=United States|isbn=0-8264-1776-0|page=58}}</ref> The opening lyrics, ''\"Teenage angst has paid off well, now I'm bored and old,\"'' were a commentary on Cobain's public image, and his life as a celebrity since the unexpected success of Nirvana's second album, ''[[Nevermind]]'', released in September 1991.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G.|title=In Utero|date=2006|publisher=Continium|location=United States|isbn=0-8264-1776-0|page=58}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Crawford |first=Anwen |date=2014 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jz5iBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT79&dq=Nirvana+Serve+the+Servants&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUhMGOkqTeAhWMYlAKHelzB804KBDoAQhTMAg#v=onepage&q=Nirvana%20Serve%20the%20Servants&f=false |title=Hole's Live Through This |page=(no page numbers) | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA |accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> The lyric, ''\"If she floats then she is not a witch like we had thought\"'', was an attack on the media for its perceived misrepresentation of Cobain's wife [[Courtney Love]], vocalist and guitarist of the American rock band [[Hole (band)|Hole]], comparing her treatment to a [[witchhunt]] and the practice of subjecting women accused of [[witchcraft]] to a public [[dunking|ordeal by water]].<ref name=\"Crisafulli\"/>\n\nIn his 1993 biography ''[[Come as You Are: The Story of Nirvana]]'', [[Michael Azerrad]] stated that Cobain sent a personal and direct message to his father with the lines, ''\"I tried hard to have a father/but instead I had a dad/I just want you to know that I don't hate you anymore/There is nothing I could say that I haven't thought before\"''.<ref name=\"Azerrad\">{{cite book |last=Azerrad |first=Michael |date=1993 |title=Come as You Are: The Story of Nirvana |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qrSDPW6G5ZIC&pg=PA326&dq=Nirvana+Serve+the+Servants&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiar5TFkaTeAhXPmLQKHZyCDtQ4HhDoAQhcMAk#v=onepage&q=Nirvana%20Serve%20the%20Servants&f=false |page=326 |publisher=Crown/Archetype|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> However, Cobain stated that the lines were included at the last minute and that \"they just happen to fit really well\".<ref name=\"Azerrad\"/> Author [[Charles R. Cross]], in his 2001 Cobain biography, ''[[Heavier Than Heaven]]'', also described these lines as bitter lyrics aimed at Cobain's father.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cross |first=Charles. R |date=2012 |title=Heavier Than Heaven |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NWOLAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Nirvana+Serve+the+Servants&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSstn-j6TeAhUQY1AKHeksAPAQ6AEIUzAJ#v=onepage&q=Serve%20the%20Servants&f=false |page=(no page numbers) |publisher=[[Hachette UK]]|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> The last line of the chorus ''\"that legendary divorce is such a bore\"'' refers to Cobain being tired of his childhood being plumbed for deep meaning.<ref name=\"Crisafulli\"/>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n\nAccording to the April 2000 edition of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', at one point during Cobain's memorial vigil in April 1994, the song was being \"blasted\" from the loudspeakers while \"an estimated 5,000 kids poured over the fountain, plugging up the spigots, lifting their middle fingers to the skies and howling with gleeful rage.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Weisbard |first=Eric |title=Spin magazine - Nirvana |date=April 2000 |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UMvcbE3u_GkC&pg=PA71&dq=Nirvana+Serve+the+Servants&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSstn-j6TeAhUQY1AKHeksAPAQ6AEIRjAG#v=onepage&q=Nirvana%20Serve%20the%20Servants&f=false |volume=16, No. 4 | publisher=SPIN Media LLC |accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked \"Serve the Servants\" at number 14 in their list of the top 102 Nirvana songs.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=No Apologies: All 102 Nirvana Songs Ranked |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/no-apologies-all-102-nirvana-songs-ranked-175683/serve-the-servants-33723/ |date=2015 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Love named \"Serve the Servants\" as one of her favorite Nirvana songs, also mentioning the ''In Utero'' songs \"[[Heart-Shaped Box]]\" and \"Frances Farmer Will Have Her Revenge on Seattle\", and the ''Nevermind'' song \"[[In Bloom]].\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Moore |first=Sam |date=May 8, 2017 |title=Courtney Love reveals her favourite Nirvana songs |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/courtney-love-reveals-favourite-nirvana-songs-2068017 |website=nme.com |publisher=[[NME]] |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe song's title is referenced by Nirvana's manager Danny Goldberg in the title of his book ''Serving The Servant: Remembering Kurt Cobain'', to be released in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cowdery |first=Katherine |date=August 14, 2018 |title=Former manager pens Kurt Cobain biography for Trapeze |url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/trapeze-publish-biography-kurt-cobain-former-manager-845756 |accessdate=January 1, 2019 |website=thebookseller.com |publisher=[[The Bookseller]]}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and release history==\n===Demo and studio versions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date recorded\n!Studio\n!Producer/recorder\n!Releases\n!Personnel \n|-\n|Winter 1992\n|Cobain residence, Seattle, Washington\n|Kurt Cobain\n|''[[With the Lights Out]]'' (2004)\n|\n*[[Kurt Cobain]]: vocals, guitar<br> \n|-\n|February 12\u201326, 1993\n|[[Pachyderm Studio]], [[Cannon Falls, Minnesota|Cannon Falls]], [[Minnesota]], US\n|[[Steve Albini]]\n|''[[In Utero (album)|In Utero]]'' (1993)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain: vocals, guitar<br> \n*[[Krist Novoselic]]: bass guitar<br>\n*[[Dave Grohl]]: drums\n|}\n\n===Live versions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date recorded\n!Venue\n!Releases\n!Personnel \n|-\n|December 13, 1993\n|[[Central Waterfront, Seattle#Piers 46\u201348|Pier 48]], Seattle, Washington\n|''[[Live and Loud (Nirvana video album)|Live and Loud]]'' (2013)<br>''In Utero (super deluxe)'' (2013)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain: vocals, guitar<br> \n*Krist Novoselic: bass guitar<br>\n*Dave Grohl: drums\n*[[Pat Smear]]: guitar\n|-\n|February 23, 1994\n|''Tunnel'', ''[[RAI]], [[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n|''Live and Loud'' (2013)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain: vocals, guitar<br> \n*Krist Novoselic: bass guitar<br>\n*Dave Grohl: drums\n*Pat Smear: guitar\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nirvana}}\n[[Category:1993 songs]]\n[[Category:Nirvana (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kurt Cobain]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Steve Albini]]\n", "name_user": "QuintusPetillius", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serve_the_Servants"}
{"title_page": "Monstress (comics)", "text_new": "{{short description|Comics series by Marjorie Liu and Sana Takeda}}\n{{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|title           = Monstress\n|image           = Monstress-01.png\n|caption         = ''Monstress'' #1 cover\n|schedule        = \n|ongoing=y\n|publisher       = [[Image Comics]]\n|date            = November 2015 \u2013 present\n|issues          = 27\n|genre           = Epic Fantasy\n|main_char_team  = Maika Halfwolf <br>Kippa<br>Master Ren<br>The Monster<br>Corvin D'Oro\n|writers         = [[Marjorie Liu]]\n|artists         = [[Sana Takeda]]\n|pencillers      = \n|inkers          = \n|letterers       = Rus Wooton\n|editors         = Jennifer M. Smith\n|creators        = [[Marjorie Liu]] & [[Sana Takeda]]\n|subcat          = Image Comics\n|sort            = Monstress (comic book)\n|TPB1            = '1.''' ''Awakening\n|ISBN1           = 9781632157096\n|TPB2            = '2.''' ''The Blood\n|ISBN2           = 9781534300415\n|TPB3            = '3.''' ''Haven\n|ISBN3           = 9781534306912\n|TPB4            = '4.''' ''The Chosen\n|ISBN4           = 9781534313361\n}}\n'''''Monstress''''' is an ongoing [[epic fantasy]] comics series written by [[Marjorie Liu]] and drawn by [[Sana Takeda]], published since 2015 by the American publisher [[Image Comics]].\n\nThe comic was described by the [[Los Angeles Review of Books]] as \"ambitious as [[George R. R. Martin]] or [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]\" for its high fantasy concepts and heavy world-building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/monsters-come-home-marjorie-liu-sana-takedas-monstress/|title=Monsters Come Home: On Marjorie Liu and Sana Takeda\u2019s \u201cMonstress\u201d|last=Song|first=Min Hyoung|website=Los Angeles Review of Books|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> The series has earned many awards, including five [[Eisner Award|Eisner Awards]], four [[Hugo Award|Hugo Awards]], and the [[List of Harvey Award winners|Harvey Awards]] Book of the Year in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/newsbrief/index.html?record=2036|title=Publisher's Weekly|last=|first=|date=|website=www.publishersweekly.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n== Summary ==\nThe series is set in a [[matriarchal]] world inspired by early 20th century Asia, and tells the story of Maika Halfwolf, a teenage girl who shares a mysterious psychic link with a powerful monster.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marjorie Liu |last1=Liu|first1=Marjorie|url=http://marjoriemliu.com/|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Cruz\">{{cite news|last1=Cruz|first1=Lenika|title=Marjorie Liu on the Road to Making 'Monstress'|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/marjorie-liu-monstress-interview/539394/|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Atlantic}}</ref> The background to the story is a war between the Arcanics, magical creatures who sometimes can pass for human, and the Cumaea, an order of sorceresses who consume Arcanics to fuel their power. Maika is an Arcanic who looks human, and who is set on learning about and avenging her dead mother. Maika's left arm has been severed and a demon occasionally emerges from its stub.<ref name=\"JT\">{{cite news|last1=Kelts|first1=Roland|title=Breaking the comic book glass ceiling|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2017/03/18/general/breaking-comic-book-glass-ceiling/#.WmoQLLBG1aS|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Japan Times|date=19 March 2017}}[http://www.sanatakeda.com/17361773_10155153431077053_2235665766323301491_n.jpg image]</ref> The demon, who takes over her body and mind, is a source of great power, but challenging for Maika to understand and control.<ref name=\"Cruz\" /> \n\nLiu first introduced the story to Takeda in 2013. The two started working together a year later, and the first issue was published in November 2015; the trade paperback first volume in July 2016, the second in July 2017,<ref name=JT/> the third in September 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-3-tp|title=Monstress, Vol. 3 TP|website=Image Comics|language=en|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> and the fourth in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imagecomics.com/comics/releases/monstress-vol-4-tp|title=Monstress, Vol. 4 TP|website=Image Comics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== Publication history ==\n[[Marjorie Liu|Liu]] has said that she struggled with depression before writing ''Monstress''. She had taken a hiatus from writing before returning to the industry with Image Comics.<ref name=TheAtlantic>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/marjorie-liu-monstress-interview/539394/|title=Marjorie Liu on the Road to Making 'Monstress'|last=Cruz|first=Lenika|date=2017-09-14|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\nShe has described the comic as \"a huge epic fantasy.\" As such, the story required world-building. The first issue was triple-sized (70 pages) in order to properly introduce the various characters and factions.<ref name=TheAtlantic/>\n\nLiu and Takeda first worked together on Liu's run of ''[[X-23]]'' for [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]]. Liu would later describe her work with Takeda as \"a wonderful process; it felt like she was reading my mind.\" A native of Japan, Takeda's art takes inspiration from [[manga]].<ref name=TheAtlantic/>\n\n== Themes ==\n[[File:5.30.19MarjorieLiuByLuigiNovi51.jpg|thumb|left|Liu at a 2019 signing for ''Monstress'' #24 at [[Midtown Comics]] in Manhattan]]\nAccording to Liu, among the series's themes are the inner strength required to withstand constant dehumanization, as well as the power of friendship among women.<ref name=HollywoodReporter>{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Graeme|title='Monstress': Inside The Fantasy Comic About Race, Feminism And The Monster Within|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/monstress-inside-fantasy-comic-race-836391|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=3 November 2015}}</ref> Race also plays a large role in the series. In the series the Arcanics, a race of magical creatures, have been at war with humans for decades, and they are now at a stalemate; however the humans are taking Arcanics and selling them as slaves to other humans.<ref name=HollywoodReporter/>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe first, triple-sized issue of ''Monstress'' received critical praise. Writing for ''[[Kotaku]]'', Evan Narcisse called it \"a gorgeous comic book about racism, war and slavery\", noting the intricate detail of Takeda's [[manga]]-inspired art.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Narcisse|first1=Evan|title=Monstress Is A Gorgeous Comic Book About Racism, War and Slavery|url=http://kotaku.com/monstress-is-a-gorgeous-comic-book-about-racism-war-an-1744178284|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=Kotaku|date=23 November 2015}}</ref> Reviewing the book for [[The A.V. Club]], Caitlin Rosberg described the leading characters, all women, as \"deeply flawed and showing layers of nuanced characterization that you don\u2019t often see in comic books\", and appreciated the series's \"sense of in-between-ness\u2014(...) neither traditionally Western nor manga, paced like a novel but drawn like a comic\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosberg|first1=Caitlin|title=Monstress captivates with its fusion of Western comics and manga|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/monstress-captivates-its-fusion-western-comics-and-227787|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=A.V. Club|date=10 November 2015}}</ref>{{-}}\n\n===Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!Award\n!Year\n!Category\n!Nominee\n!Result\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[British Fantasy Award]]\n|2017<ref name=\"BFA 2017\">{{cite web|title=Announcing the 2017 British Fantasy Award Winners|url=https://www.tor.com/2017/10/01/announcing-the-2017-british-fantasy-award-winners/|website=Tor|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Comic / Graphic Novel\n|